# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/abisares] Abisares sent embassies of submission to Alexander the Great and Alexander allowed him to retain his kingdom with considerable additions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/abisares] Onesicritus said that Abisares had two huge snakes and Alexander had a great desire to see them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/abisares] Aurel Stein equates the Hazara region, frequently identified as the ancient Urasa with Abhisara.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/abisares] However, Stein identifies the kingdom of Abhisara with the tract of the lower and middle hills between the Vitasta (Jhelum) and Chadrabhaga (Chenab) including the state of Rajapuri (Rajauri) in Kasmira.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/abisares] Old kingdom of Abhisara was basically situated in the Poonch, Rajauri and Nowshera districts of Jammu and Kashmir.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Around 535 BCE, the Persian king Cyrus the Great initiated a protracted campaign to absorb parts of northwestern Indian subcontinent into his nascent Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] In this initial incursion, the Persian army annexed a large region to the west of the Indus River, consolidating the early eastern borders of their new realm.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] With a brief pause after Cyrus' death around 530 BCE, the campaign continued under Darius the Great, who began to re-conquer former provinces and further expand the Achaemenid Empire's political boundaries.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Around 518 BCE, the Persian army pushed further into India to initiate a second period of conquest by annexing regions up to the Jhelum River in what is today known as Punjab.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] At peak, the Persians managed to take control of most of modern-day Pakistan and incorporate it into their territory.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The first secure epigraphic evidence through the Behistun Inscription gives a date before or around 518 BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Persian penetration into the Indian subcontinent occurred in multiple stages, beginning from the northern parts of the Indus River and moving southward.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] As mentioned in several Achaemenid-era inscriptions, the Indus Valley was formally incorporated into the Persian realm through provincial divisions: Gandāra, Hindush, and Sattagydia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Persian rule over the Indus Valley decreased over successive rulers and formally ended with the Greek conquest of Persia, led by Alexander the Great.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] This brief period gave rise to independent Indian kings, such as Abisares, Porus, and Ambhi, as well as numerous *gaṇasaṅghas*, which would later confront the Macedonian army as it massed into the region for Alexander's Indian campaign.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Achaemenid Empire set a precedence of governance through the use of satrapies, which was further implemented by Alexander's Macedonian Empire, the Indo-Scythians, and the Kushan Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] For millennia, the northwestern part of India had maintained some level of trade relations with the Near East.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Finally, the Achaemenid Empire underwent a considerable expansion, both east and west, during the reign of Cyrus the Great (c.600–530 BC), leading the dynasty to take a direct interest into the region of northwestern India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The conquest is often thought to have started circa 535 BCE, during the time of Cyrus the Great (600-530 BCE).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Province was also referred to as *Paruparaesanna* (Greek: Parapamisadae) in the Babylonian and Elamite versions of the Behistun inscription.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The geographical extent of this province was wider than the Indian Gandhara.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Various accounts, such as those of Xenophon or Ctesias, who wrote *Indica*, also suggest that Cyrus conquered parts of India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Another Indian Province was conquered named Sattagydia (𐎰𐎫𐎦𐎢𐏁, *Thataguš*) in the Behistun inscription.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] It was probably contiguous to Gandhara, but its actual location is uncertain.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Fleming locates it between Arachosia and the middle Indus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Fleming also mentions Maka, in the area of Gedrosia, as one of the Indian satrapies.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] A successor of Cyrus the Great, Darius I was back in 518 BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The date of 518 BCE is given by the Behistun inscription, and is also often the one given for the secure occupation of Gandhara in Punjab.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Hamadan Gold and Silver Tablet inscription of Darius I also refers to his conquests in India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The exact area of the Province of *Hindush* is uncertain.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Alternatively, *Hindush* may have been the region of Taxila and Western Punjab, where there are indications that a Persian satrapy may have existed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] According to Herodotus, Darius I sent the Greek explorer Scylax of Caryanda to sail down the Indus River, heading a team of spies, in order to explore the course of the Indus River.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] After a periplus of 30 months, Scylax is said to have returned to Egypt near the Red Sea, and the seas between the Near East and India were made use of by Darius.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Also according to Herodotus, the territories of Gandhara, Sattagydia, Dadicae and Aparytae formed the 7th province of the Achaemenid Empire for tax-payment purposes, while *Indus* (called *Ἰνδός*, "Indos" in Greek sources) formed the 20th tax region.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Throughout its existence, the Achaemenid were constantly engaging in wars.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Either through conquering new territories or by quelling rebellions throughout the empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] To fulfil this need, the Achaemenid Empire had to maintain a professional standing army which levied and employed personnel from all of its satraps and territories.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Achaemenid army was not uniquely Persian.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Rather it was composed of many different ethnicities that were part of the vast and diverse Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Herodotus gives a full list of the ethnicities of the Achaemenid army, in which are included Bactrians, Sakas (Scythians), Parthians, Sogdians, Ionians (Greeks), Egyptians, Ethiopians, etc.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] These ethnicities are likely to have been included in the Achaemenid army during the invasions of India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] These events were recorded in the imperial inscriptions of the Achaemenids (the Behistun inscription and the Naqsh-i-Rustam inscription, as well as the accounts of Herodotus (483–431 BCE).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Greek Scylax of Caryanda, who had been appointed by Darius I to explore the Indian Ocean from the mouth of the Indus to Suez left an account, the *Periplous*, of which fragments from secondary sources have survived.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Hecataeus of Miletus (circa 500 BCE) also wrote about the "Indus Satrapies" of the Achaemenids.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] From the dating of the Behistun inscription, it is possible to infer that the Achaemenids first conquered the areas of Gandara and Sattagydia circa 518 BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Hinduš is also mentioned as one of 24 subject countries of the Achaemenid Empire, illustrated with the drawing of a kneeling subject and a hieroglyphic cartridge reading **𓉔𓈖𓂧𓍯𓇌** (*h-n-d-wꜣ-y*), on the Egyptian Statue of Darius I, now in the National Museum of Iran.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Sattagydia also appears (**𓐠𓂧𓎼𓍯𓍒**, *sꜣ-d-g-wꜣ-ḏꜣ*, Sattagydia), and probably Gandara (**𓉔𓃭𓐍𓂧𓇌**, *h-rw-ḫ-d-y*, although this could be Arachosia), with their own illustrations.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The deposition of these foundation tablets and the Apadana coin hoard found under them, is dated to circa 515 BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The DSe inscription and DSm inscription of Darius in Susa gives *Thataguš* (Sattagydia), *Gadāra* (Gandara) and *Hiduš* (Sind) among the nations that he rules.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] — The Geography of Strabo, Book XV, Chapter 2, 9.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The nature of the administration under the Achaemenids is uncertain.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Even though the Indian provinces are called "satrapies" by convention, there is no evidence of there being any satraps in these provinces.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] When Alexander invaded the region, he did not encounter Achaemenid satraps in the Indian provinces, but local Indian rulers referred to as *hyparchs* ("Vice-Regents"), a term that connotes subordination to the Achaemenid rulers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The local rulers may have reported to the satraps of Bactria and Arachosia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Darius I listed three Indian provinces: *Sattagydia* (*Thataguš)*, *Gandāra* (Gandhara) and *Hidūš* (Sind), in which "Sind" should be understood as "Indus Valley".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Gandhara included the entire Peshawar Valley which was bound by the Swat District in the north, Afghanistan in the West, the Indus River to the south east, and Kohat District in the south.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The capital of the Gandhara satrapy was Pushkalavati.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Archeological excavations of Pushkalavati were conducted by Mortimer Wheeler in 1962 who discovered structures built during the Achaemenid period as well as artifacts.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Achaemenid Satrapy of Hindush incorporated the Greater Punjab region in the Indus Valley.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] It was bound by the Hazara region to the north, the Indus River to the west, and the Jhelum River in the south and east.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The satrapy's capital was Bhir Mound in Takshashila (Taxila).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Bhir Mound was excavated by John Marshall between 1913 and 1934.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Fortified structures and canals were found dating to the Achaemenid period, as well as ornamental jewelry.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The last known appearance of Gandhara in name as an Achaemenid province is on the list of the tomb of Artaxerxes II, circa 358 BCE, date of his burial.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Herodotus (III-91 and III-94), gives a list with a slightly different structure, as some province which are presented separately in the Achaemenid inscriptions are grouped together by Herodotus when he described the tribute paid by each territory.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Herodotus presents *Indos* (Ἰνδός) as "the 20th province", while "the Sattagydae, Gandarii, Dadicae, and Aparytae" together form "the 7th Province".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Olmstead, the fact that some Achaemenid regions are grouped together in this list may have represented some loss of territory.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The *Hindūš* province, remained loyal till Alexander's invasion.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Circa 400 BC, Ctesias of Cnidus related that the Persian king was receiving numerous gifts from the kings of "India" (*Hindūš*).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Ctesias also reported Indian elephants and Indian mahouts making demonstrations of the elephant's strength at the Achaemenid court.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] By about 380 BC, the Persian hold on the region was weakening, but the area continued to be a part of the Achaemenid Empire until Alexander's invasion.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] 380 – July 330 BC) still had Indian units in his army, albeit very few in comparison to his predecessors.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] In particular he had 15 war elephants at the Battle of Gaugamela for his fight against Alexander the Great.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The reliefs at the Apadana Palace in Persepolis describe tribute bearers from 23 satrapies visiting the Achaemenid court.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] These are located at the southern end of the Apadana Staircase.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Among the foreigners the Arabs, the Thracians, the Bactrians, the Indians (from the Indus valley area), the Parthians, the Cappadocians, the Elamites or the Medians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Indians from the Indus valley are bare-chested, except for their leader, and barefooted and wear the dhoti.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] They bring baskets with vases inside, carry axes, and drive along a donkey.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] One man in the Indian procession carries a small but visibly heavy load of four jars on a yoke, suggesting that he was carrying some of the gold dust paid by the Indians as tribute to the Achaemenid court.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] According to the Naqsh-e Rustam inscription of Darius I (circa 490 BCE), there were three Achaemenid Satrapies in the subcontinent: Sattagydia, Gandara, Hidūš.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The conquered area was the most fertile and populous region of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] An amount of tribute was fixed according to the richness of each territory.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Herodotus (who makes several comments on India) published a list of tribute-paying nations, classifying them in 20 Provinces.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Province of *Indos* (Ἰνδός, the Indus valley) formed the 20th Province, and was the richest and most populous of the Achaemenid Provinces.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The exchange rate between gold and silver at the time of Herodotus being 13 to 1, this was equal in value to the very large amount of 4680 Euboean talents of silver, equivalent to 3600 Babylonian talents of silver (equivalent in value to about 108 tons of silver annually).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The country of the "Indians" ('Ινδοι, *Indoi*) was the Achaemenid district paying the largest tribute, and alone represented 32% of the total tribute revenues of the whole Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] It also means that *Indos* was the richest Achaemenid region in the subcontinent, much richer than Gandara or Sattagydia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] However the amount of gold in question is quite enormous, so there is a possibility that Herodotus was mistaken and that his own sources actually only meant something like the gold equivalent of 360 Babylonian talents of silver.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Indians also supplied Yaka wood (teak) for the construction of Achaemenid palaces, as well as war elephants such as those used at Gaugamela.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Susa inscriptions of Darius explain that Indian ivory and teak were sold on Persian markets, and used in the construction of his palace.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Indians were employed in the Achaemenid army of Xerxes in the Second Persian invasion of Greece (480-479 BCE).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] All troops were stationed in Sardis, Lydia, during the winter of 481-480 BCE to prepare for the invasion.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] In the spring of 480 BCE "Indian troops marched with Xerxes's army across the Hellespont".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] It was the "first-ever force from India to fight on the continent of Europe", storming Greek troops at the Battle of Thermopylae in 480 BCE, and fighting as one of the main nations until the final Battle of Plataea in 479 BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] After the first part of the campaign directly under the orders Xerxes I, the Indian troops are reported to have stayed in Greece as one of the 5 main nations among the 300,000 elite troops of General Mardonius.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] At the final Battle of Plataea in 479 BCE, Indians formed one of the main corps of Achaemenid troops (one of "the greatest of the nations").
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] They were one of the main battle corps, positioned near the center of the Achaemenid battle line, between the Bactrians and the Sakae, facing against the enemy Greek troops of "Hermione and Eretria and Styra and Chalcis".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] According to modern estimates, the Bactrians, Indians and Sakae probably numbered about 20,000 men altogether, whereas the Persian troops on their left amounted to about 40,000.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] There were also Greek allies of the Persians, positioned on the right, whom Herodotus numbers at 50,000, a number which however might be "extravagant", and is nowadays estimated to around 20,000.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Indians also supplied part of the cavalry, the total of which was about 5,000.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The last Achaemenid ruler Darius III never had time to finish his own tomb due to his hasty defeat by Alexander the Great, and therefore does not have such depictions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] According to Arrian, Indian troops were still deployed under Darius III at the Battle of Gaugamela (331 BCE).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] He explains that Darius III "obtained the help of those Indians who bordered on the Bactrians, together with the Bactrians and Sogdianians themselves, all under the command of Bessus, the Satrap of Bactria".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Indians in questions were probably from the area of Gandara.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Indian "hill-men" are also said by Arrian to have joined the Arachotians under Satrap Barsentes, and are thought to have been either the Sattagydians or the Hindush.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Fifteen Indian war elephants were also part of the army of Darius III at Gaugamela.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] They had specifically been brought from India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Still, it seems they did not participate to the final battle, probably because of fatigue.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] This was a relief for the armies of Alexander, who had no previous experience of combat against war elephants.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The elephants were captured with the baggage train by the Greeks after the engagement.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Coins found in the Chaman Hazouri hoard in Kabul, the Shaikhan Dehri hoard in Pushkalavati in Gandhara, near Charsadda, as well as in the Bhir Mound hoard in Taxila, have revealed numerous Achaemenid coins as well as many Greek coins from the 5th and 4th centuries BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] These circulated in the area, at least as far as the Indus during the reign of the Achaemenids, who were in control of the areas as far as Gandhara.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Kabul hoard, also called the Chaman Hazouri, Chaman Hazouri or Tchamani-i Hazouri hoard, is a coin hoard discovered in the vicinity of Kabul, Afghanistan.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The hoard, discovered in 1933, contained numerous Achaemenid coins as well as many Greek coins from the 5th and 4th centuries BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Approximately one thousand coins were in the hoard.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The hoard is dated to approximately 380 BCE as no coins in the hoard were later than that date.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] This numismatic discovery has been very important in studying and dating the history of coinage of India, since it is one of the very rare instances when punch-marked coins can actually be dated, due to their association with known and dated Greek and Achaemenid coins in the hoard.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The hoard supports the view that punch-marked coins existed in 360 BCE, as suggested by literary evidence.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] — Daniel Schlumberger, quoted from Trésors Monétaires, p.42.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Modern numismatists now tend to consider the Achaemenid punch-marked coins as the precursors of the Indian punch-marked coins.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] In 2007, a small coin hoard was discovered at the site of ancient Pushkalavati (the Shaikhan Dehri hoard) near Charsada in Pakistan.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The hoard contained a tetradrachm minted in Athens circa 500/490-485/0 BCE, typically used as a currency for trade in the Achaemenid Empire, together with a number of local types as well as silver cast ingots.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Athens coin is the earliest known example of its type to be found so far to the east.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] According to Joe Cribb, these early Greek coins were at the origin of Indian punch-marked coins, the earliest coins developed in India, which used minting technology derived from Greek coinage.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Various Indian artefacts tend to suggest some Perso-Hellenistic artistic influence in India, mainly felt during the time of the Mauryan Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The sculpture of the Masarh lion, found near the Maurya capital of Pataliputra, raises the question of the Achaemenid and Greek influence on the art of the Maurya Empire, and on the western origins of stone carving in India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The lion is carved in Chunar sandstone, like the Pillars of Ashoka, and its finish is polished, a feature of the Maurya sculpture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Gupta, the sculptural style is unquestionably Achaemenid.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] This is particularly the case for the well-ordered tubular representation of whiskers (vibrissas) and the geometrical representation of inflated veins flush with the entire face.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The mane, on the other hand, with tufts of hair represented in wavelets, is rather naturalistic.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Very similar examples are however known in Greece and Persepolis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Pataliputra palace with its pillared hall shows decorative influences of the Achaemenid palaces and Persepolis and may have used the help of foreign craftsmen.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Mauryan rulers may have even imported craftsmen from abroad to build royal monuments.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] This may be the result of the formative influence of craftsmen employed from Persia following the disintegration of the Achaemenid Empire after the conquests of Alexander the Great.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The Pataliputra capital, or also the Hellenistic friezes of the Rampurva capitals, Sankissa, and the diamond throne of Bodh Gaya are other examples.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] The renowned Mauryan polish, especially used in the Pillars of Ashoka, may also have been a technique imported from the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] "Persian Nobleman clad in coat dupatta trouser and turban", Mathura, c.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Some relatively high quality terracotta statuettes have been recovered from the Mauryan Empire strata in the excavations of Mathura in northern India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Most of these terracottas show what appears to be female deities or mother goddesses.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] However, several figures of foreigners also appear in the terracottas from the 4th to the 2nd century BCE, which are either described simply as "foreigners" or Persian or Iranian because of their foreign features.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] These figurines might reflect the increased contacts of Indians with Iranian people during this period.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Several of these seem to represent foreign soldiers who visited India during the Mauryan period and influenced modellers in Mathura with their peculiar ethnic features and uniforms.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] One of the terracotta statuettes, a man nicknamed the "Persian nobleman" and dated to the 2nd century BCE, can be seen wearing a coat, scarf, trousers and a turban.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] In ancient sources, Hystapes is sometimes considered as identical with Vishtaspa (the Avestan and Old Persian name for Hystapes), an early patron of Zoroaster.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/achaemenid-conquest-of-the-indus-valley] Beckwith's methodologies and interpretations concerning early Buddhism, inscriptions, and archaeological sites have been criticized by other scholars, such as Johannes Bronkhorst, Osmund Bopearachchi, Stephen Batchelor and Charles Goodman.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The **Ajanta Caves** are 30 rock-cut Buddhist cave monuments dating from the second century BCE to about 480 CE in Aurangabad district of Maharashtra state in India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Ajanta Caves are a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Universally regarded as masterpieces of Buddhist religious art, the caves include paintings and rock-cut sculptures, described as among the finest surviving examples of ancient Indian art, particularly expressive paintings that present emotions through gesture, pose and form.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves were built in two phases, the first starting around the second century BCE and the second occurring from 400 to 650 CE, according to older accounts, or in a brief period of 460–480 CE according to later scholarship.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves constitute ancient monasteries (*Viharas*) and worship-halls (*Chaityas*) of different Buddhist traditions carved into a 75-metre (246 ft) wall of rock.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves also present paintings depicting the past lives and rebirths of the Buddha, pictorial tales from *Aryasura's Jatakamala*, and rock-cut sculptures of Buddhist deities.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Textual records suggest that these caves served as a monsoon retreat for monks, as well as a resting site for merchants and pilgrims in ancient India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] While vivid colours and mural wall paintings were abundant in Indian history as evidenced by historical records, Caves 1, 2, 16 and 17 of Ajanta form the largest corpus of surviving ancient Indian wall-paintings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves are mentioned in the memoirs of several medieval-era Chinese Buddhist travelers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] They were covered by the jungle until accidentally "discovered" and brought to contemporary attention in 1819 by Colonel John Smith during a tiger-hunting expedition on a tiger-hunting party.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves are located in the rocky northern wall of the U-shaped gorge of the River Waghur, in the Deccan Plateau.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Within the gorge are a number of waterfalls, audible from outside the caves when the river is high.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Ajanta is one of the major tourist attractions of Maharashtra.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It is about 59 kilometres (37 miles) from the city of Jalgaon, Maharashtra, India, 104 kilometres (65 miles) from the city of Aurangabad, and 350 kilometres (220 miles) east-northeast of Mumbai.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] There are Ellora Caves another UNESCO World Heritage Site, which is 100 Kilometres (62 miles) contains Hindu, Jain, and Buddhist caves, the last dating from a period similar to Ajanta.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta style is also found in the Ellora Caves and other near about caves such as the Elephanta Caves, Aurangabad Caves, Shivleni Caves and the cave temples of Karnataka.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Nearest airports are Jalgaon and Sambhaji Nagar, followed by Mumbai, and nearest railway stations are Jalgaon and Bhusawal.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves are generally agreed to have been made in two distinct phases; first during the 2nd century BCE to 1st century CE, and second several centuries later.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves consist of 36 identifiable foundations, some of them discovered after the original numbering of the caves from 1 through 29.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The later-identified caves have been suffixed with the letters of the alphabet, such as 15A, identified between originally numbered caves 15 and 16.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave numbering is a convention of convenience and does not reflect the chronological order of their construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The earliest group consists of caves 9, 10, 12, 13 and 15 A.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The murals in these caves depict stories from the Jatakas.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Later caves reflect the artistic influence of the Gupta period, but there are differing opinions on which century in which the early caves were built.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Walter Spink, they were made during the period 100 BCE to 100 CE, probably under the patronage of the Satavahana dynasty (230 BCE – 220 CE) who ruled the region.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Other datings prefer the period of the Maurya Empire (300 BCE to 100 BCE).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Of these, caves 9 and 10 are stupa containing worship halls of *chaitya-griha* form, and caves 12, 13, and 15A are *vihāras* (see the architecture section below for descriptions of these types).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The first Satavahana period caves lacked figurative sculpture, emphasizing the stupa instead.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, once the Satavahana period caves were made, the site was not further developed for a considerable period until the mid-5th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] However, the early caves were in use during this dormant period, and Buddhist pilgrims visited the site, according to the records left by Chinese pilgrim Faxian around 400 CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The second phase of construction at the Ajanta Caves site began in the 5th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] For a long time it was thought that the later caves were made over an extended period from the 4th to the 7th centuries CE, but in recent decades a series of studies by the leading expert on the caves, Walter M.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink, have argued that most of the work took place over the very brief period from 460 to 480 CE, during the reign of Hindu Emperor Harishena of the Vākāṭaka dynasty.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This view has been criticised by some scholars, but is now broadly accepted by most authors of general books on Indian art, for example, Huntington and Harle.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The second phase is attributed to the theistic Mahāyāna, or Greater Vehicle tradition of Buddhism.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Caves of the second period are 1–8, 11, 14–29, some possibly extensions of earlier caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Caves 19, 26, and 29 are *chaitya-grihas*, the rest *viharas*.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The most elaborate caves were produced in this period, which included some refurbishing and repainting of the early caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink states that it is possible to establish dating for this period with a very high level of precision; a fuller account of his chronology is given below.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Although debate continues, Spink's ideas are increasingly widely accepted, at least in their broad conclusions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Archaeological Survey of India website still presents the traditional dating: "The second phase of paintings started around 5th–6th centuries A.D. and continued for the next two centuries".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, the construction activity at the incomplete Ajanta Caves was abandoned by wealthy patrons in about 480 CE, a few years after the death of Harishena.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] However, states Spink, the caves appear to have been in use for a period of time as evidenced by the wear of the pivot holes in caves constructed close to 480 CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The second phase of constructions and decorations at Ajanta corresponds to the very apogee of Classical India, or India's golden age.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] However, at that time, the Gupta Empire was already weakening from internal political issues and from the assaults of the Hūṇas, so that the Vakatakas were actually one of the most powerful empires in India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Some of the Hūṇas, the Alchon Huns of Toramana, were precisely ruling the neighbouring area of Malwa, at the doorstep of the Western Deccan, at the time the Ajanta Caves were made.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Richard Cohen, a description of the caves by 7th-century Chinese Traveller Xuanzang and scattered medieval graffiti suggest that the Ajanta Caves were known and probably in use subsequently, but without a stable or steady Buddhist community presence.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta caves are mentioned in the 17th-century text *Ain-i-Akbari* by Abu al-Fazl, as twenty four rock-cut cave temples each with remarkable idols.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] On 28 April 1819 a British officer named John Smith, of the 28th Cavalry, while hunting tigers was shown the entrance to Cave No.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] 10 when a local shepherd boy guided him to the location and the door.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves were well known by locals already.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Captain Smith went to a nearby village and asked the villagers to come to the site with axes, spears, torches, and drums, to cut down the tangled jungle growth that made entering the cave difficult.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] He first saw ceilings with beautiful and artistically drawn faces on them, then he noticed monastic halls which helped him identify their Buddhist origin.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] He then deliberately damaged an image on the wall by scratching his name and the date over the painting of a bodhisattva.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Since he stood on a five-foot high pile of rubble collected over the years, the inscription is well above the eye-level gaze of an adult today.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] A paper on the caves by William Erskine was read to the Bombay Literary Society in 1822.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Within a few decades, the caves became famous for their exotic setting, impressive architecture, and above all their exceptional and unique paintings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] A number of large projects to copy the paintings were made in the century after rediscovery.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] In 1848, the Royal Asiatic Society established the "Bombay Cave Temple Commission" to clear, tidy and record the most important rock-cut sites in the Bombay Presidency, with John Wilson as president.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] In 1861 this became the nucleus of the new Archaeological Survey of India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] During the colonial era, the Ajanta site was in the territory of the princely state of the Hyderabad and not British India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] In the early 1920s, Mir Osman Ali Khan, the last Nizam of Hyderabad, appointed people to restore the artwork, converted the site into a museum and built a road to bring tourists to the site for a fee.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These efforts resulted in early mismanagement, states Richard Cohen, and hastened the deterioration of the site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Post-independence, the state government of Maharashtra built arrival, transport, facilities, and better site management.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The modern Visitor Center has good parking facilities and public conveniences and ASI operated buses run at regular intervals from Visitor Center to the caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Nizam's Director of Archaeology obtained the services of two experts from Italy, Professor Lorenzo Cecconi, assisted by Count Orsini, to restore the paintings in the caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Despite these efforts, later neglect led to the paintings degrading in quality once again.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Since 1983, Ajanta caves have been listed among the UNESCO World Heritage Sites of India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves, along with the Ellora Caves, have become the most popular tourist destination in Maharashtra, and are often crowded at holiday times, increasing the threat to the caves, especially the paintings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves are carved out of flood basalt and granite rock of a cliff, part of the Deccan Traps formed by successive volcanic eruptions at the end of the Cretaceous geological period.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The rock is layered horizontally, and somewhat variable in quality.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This variation within the rock layers required the artists to amend their carving methods and plans in places.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The inhomogeneity in the rock has also led to cracks and collapses in the centuries that followed, as with the lost portico to cave 1.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Excavation began by cutting a narrow tunnel at roof level, which was expanded downwards and outwards; as evidenced by some of the incomplete caves such as the partially-built *vihara* caves 21 through 24 and the abandoned incomplete cave 28.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The sculpture artists likely worked at both excavating the rocks and making the intricate carvings of pillars, roof, and idols; further, the sculpture and painting work inside a cave were integrated parallel tasks.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] A grand gateway to the site was carved, at the apex of the gorge's horseshoe between caves 15 and 16, as approached from the river, and it is decorated with elephants on either side and a nāga, or protective Naga (snake) deity.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Similar methods and application of artist talent is observed in other cave temples of India, such as those from Hinduism and Jainism.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These include the Ellora Caves, Ghatotkacha Caves, Elephanta Caves, Bagh Caves, Badami Caves, Aurangabad Caves and Shivleni Caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The caves from the first period seem to have been paid for by a number of different patrons to gain merit, with several inscriptions recording the donation of particular portions of a single cave.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The later caves were each commissioned as a complete unit by a single patron from the local rulers or their court elites, again for merit in Buddhist afterlife beliefs as evidenced by inscriptions such as those in Cave 17.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The majority of the caves are *vihara* halls with symmetrical square plans.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] To each vihara hall are attached smaller square dormitory cells cut into the walls.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This change reflects the shift from Hinayana to Mahāyāna Buddhism.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These caves are often called monasteries.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The central square space of the interior of the viharas is defined by square columns forming a more-or-less square open area.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Outside this are long rectangular aisles on each side, forming a kind of cloister.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Along the side and rear walls are a number of small cells entered by a narrow doorway; these are roughly square, and have small niches on their back walls.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The centre of the rear wall has a larger shrine-room behind, containing a large Buddha statue.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The viharas of the earlier period are much simpler, and lack shrines.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink places the change to a design with a shrine to the middle of the second period, with many caves being adapted to add a shrine in mid-excavation, or after the original phase.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The plan of Cave 1 shows one of the largest viharas, but is fairly typical of the later group.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Many others, such as Cave 16, lack the vestibule to the shrine, which leads straight off the main hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 6 is two viharas, one above the other, connected by internal stairs, with sanctuaries on both levels.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Top: Interior of Ajanta chaitya hall, Cave 26, photo by Robert Gill (c.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] 1868); Bottom: James Fergusson sketch of Cave 19 worship hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The other type of main hall architecture is the narrower rectangular plan with high arched ceiling type *chaitya-griha* – literally, "the house of stupa".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This hall is longitudinally divided into a nave and two narrower side aisles separated by a symmetrical row of pillars, with a stupa in the apse.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The stupa is surrounded by pillars and concentric walking space for circumambulation.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Some of the caves have elaborate carved entrances, some with large windows over the door to admit light.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] There is often a colonnaded porch or verandah, with another space inside the doors running the width of the cave.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The oldest worship halls at Ajanta were built in the 2nd to 1st century BCE, the newest ones in the late 5th century CE, and the architecture of both resembles the architecture of a Christian church, but without the crossing or chapel chevette.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves follow the Cathedral-style architecture found in still older rock-cut cave carvings of ancient India, such as the Lomas Rishi Cave of the Ajivikas near Gaya in Bihar dated to the 3rd century BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These chaitya-griha are called worship or prayer halls.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The four completed *chaitya* halls are caves 9 and 10 from the early period, and caves 19 and 26 from the later period of construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] All follow the typical form found elsewhere, with high ceilings and a central "nave" leading to the stupa, which is near the back, but allows walking behind it, as walking around stupas was (and remains) a common element of Buddhist worship (*pradakshina*).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The later two have high ribbed roofs carved into the rock, which reflect timber forms, and the earlier two are thought to have used actual timber ribs and are now smooth, the original wood presumed to have perished.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The two later halls have a rather unusual arrangement (also found in Cave 10 at Ellora) where the stupa is fronted by a large relief sculpture of the Buddha, standing in Cave 19 and seated in Cave 26.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 29 is a late and very incomplete *chaitya* hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The form of columns in the work of the first period is very plain and un-embellished, with both *chaitya* halls using simple octagonal columns, which were later painted with images of the Buddha, people and monks in robes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] In the second period columns were far more varied and inventive, often changing profile over their height, and with elaborate carved capitals, often spreading wide.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Many columns are carved over all their surface with floral motifs and Mahayana deities, some fluted and others carved with decoration all over, as in cave 1.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Most of the Ajanta caves, and almost all the murals paintings date from nearly 600 years later, during a second phase of construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings in the Ajanta caves predominantly narrate the Jataka tales.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These are Buddhist legends describing the previous births of the Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These fables embed ancient morals and cultural lores that are also found in the fables and legends of Hindu and Jain texts.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Jataka tales are exemplified through the life example and sacrifices that the Buddha made in hundreds of his past incarnations, where he is depicted as having been reborn as an animal or human.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Mural paintings survive from both the earlier and later groups of caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Some connections with the art of Gandhara can also be noted, and there is evidence of a shared artistic idiom.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Four of the later caves have large and relatively well-preserved mural paintings which, states James Harle, "have come to represent Indian mural painting to the non-specialist", and represent "the great glories not only of Gupta but of all Indian art".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] They fall into two stylistic groups, with the most famous in Caves 16 and 17, and apparently later paintings in Caves 1 and 2.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The latter group were thought to be a century or later than the others, but the revised chronology proposed by Spink would place them in the 5th century as well, perhaps contemporary with it in a more progressive style, or one reflecting a team from a different region.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta frescos are classical paintings and the work of confident artists, without cliches, rich and full.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] They are luxurious, sensuous and celebrate physical beauty, aspects that early Western observers felt were shockingly out of place in these caves presumed to be meant for religious worship and ascetic monastic life.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings are in "dry fresco", painted on top of a dry plaster surface rather than into wet plaster.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] All the paintings appear to be the work of painters supported by discriminating connoisseurship and sophisticated patrons from an urban atmosphere.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It is known from literary sources that painting was widely practised and appreciated in the Gupta period.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Unlike much Indian mural painting, compositions are not laid out in horizontal bands like a frieze, but show large scenes spreading in all directions from a single figure or group at the centre.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The ceilings are also painted with sophisticated and elaborate decorative motifs, many derived from sculpture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings in cave 1, which according to Spink was commissioned by Harisena himself, concentrate on those Jataka tales which show previous lives of the Buddha as a king, rather than as deer or elephant or another Jataka animal.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The scenes depict the Buddha as about to renounce the royal life.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] In general the later caves seem to have been painted on finished areas as excavating work continued elsewhere in the cave, as shown in caves 2 and 16 in particular.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink's account of the chronology of the caves, the abandonment of work in 478 after a brief busy period accounts for the absence of painting in places including cave 4 and the shrine of cave 17, the later being plastered in preparation for paintings that were never done.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Walter Spink has over recent decades developed a very precise and circumstantial chronology for the second period of work on the site, which unlike earlier scholars, he places entirely in the 5th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This is based on evidence such as the inscriptions and artistic style, dating of nearby cave temple sites, comparative chronology of the dynasties, combined with the many uncompleted elements of the caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] He believes the earlier group of caves, which like other scholars he dates only approximately, to the period "between 100 BCE – 100 CE", were at some later point completely abandoned and remained so "for over three centuries".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This changed during the Hindu emperor Harishena of the Vakataka Dynasty, who reigned from 460 to his death in 477, who sponsored numerous new caves during his reign.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Harisena's rule extended the Central Indian Vakataka Empire to include a stretch of the east coast of India; the Gupta Empire ruled northern India at the same period, and the Pallava dynasty much of the south.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, Harishena encouraged a group of associates, including his prime minister Varahadeva and Upendragupta, the sub-king in whose territory Ajanta was, to dig out new caves, which were individually commissioned, some containing inscriptions recording the donation.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This activity began in many caves simultaneously about 462.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This activity was mostly suspended in 468 because of threats from the neighbouring Asmaka kings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Thereafter work continued on only Caves 1, Harisena's own commission, and 17–20, commissioned by Upendragupta.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] In 472 the situation was such that work was suspended completely, in a period that Spink calls "the Hiatus", which lasted until about 475, by which time the Asmakas had replaced Upendragupta as the local rulers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Work was then resumed, but again disrupted by Harisena's death in 477, soon after which major excavation ceased, except at cave 26, which the Asmakas were sponsoring themselves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Asmakas launched a revolt against Harisena's son, which brought about the end of the Vakataka Dynasty.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] In the years 478–480 CE major excavation by important patrons was replaced by a rash of "intrusions" – statues added to existing caves, and small shrines dotted about where there was space between them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These were commissioned by less powerful individuals, some monks, who had not previously been able to make additions to the large excavations of the rulers and courtiers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] They were added to the facades, the return sides of the entrances, and to walls inside the caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, "After 480, not a single image was ever made again at the site".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] However, there exists a Rashtrakuta inscription outside of cave 26 dateable to end of seventh or early 8th century, suggesting the caves were not abandoned until then.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink does not use "circa" in his dates, but says that "one should allow a margin of error of one year or perhaps even two in all cases".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Ajanta Caves were built in a period when both the Buddha and the Hindu gods were simultaneously revered in Indian culture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink and other scholars, the royal Vakataka sponsors of the Ajanta Caves probably worshipped both Hindu and Buddhist gods.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This is evidenced by inscriptions in which these rulers, who are otherwise known as Hindu devotees, made Buddhist dedications to the caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] A terracotta plaque of Mahishasuramardini, also known as Durga, was also found in a burnt-brick vihara monastery facing the caves on the right bank of the river Waghora that has been recently excavated.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This suggest that the deity was possibly under worship by the artisans.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Yuko Yokoschi and Walter Spink, the excavated artifacts of the 5th century near the site suggest that the Ajanta caves deployed a huge number of builders.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 1 was built on the eastern end of the horseshoe-shaped scarp and is now the first cave the visitor encounters.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This cave, when first made, would have been in a less prominent position, right at the end of the row.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, it is one of the last caves to have been excavated, when the best sites had been taken, and was never fully inaugurated for worship by the dedication of the Buddha image in the central shrine.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This is shown by the absence of sooty deposits from butter lamps on the base of the shrine image, and the lack of damage to the paintings that would have happened if the garland-hooks around the shrine had been in use for any period of time.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink states that the Vākāṭaka Emperor Harishena was the benefactor of the work, and this is reflected in the emphasis on imagery of royalty in the cave, with those Jataka tales being selected that tell of those previous lives of the Buddha in which he was royal.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cliff has a steeper slope here than at other caves, so to achieve a tall grand facade it was necessary to cut far back into the slope, giving a large courtyard in front of the facade.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] There was originally a columned portico in front of the present facade, which can be seen "half-intact in the 1880s" in pictures of the site, but this fell down completely and the remains, despite containing fine carvings, were carelessly thrown down the slope into the river and lost.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This cave (35.7 m × 27.6 m) has one of the most elaborate carved facades, with relief sculptures on entablature and ridges, and most surfaces embellished with decorative carving.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] There are scenes carved from the life of the Buddha as well as a number of decorative motifs.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] A two-pillared portico, visible in the 19th-century photographs, has since perished.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a forecourt with cells fronted by pillared vestibules on either side.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a porch with simple cells at both ends.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The absence of pillared vestibules on the ends suggests that the porch was not excavated in the latest phase of Ajanta when pillared vestibules had become customary.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Most areas of the porch were once covered with murals, of which many fragments remain, especially on the ceiling.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] There are three doorways: a central doorway and two side doorways.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Two square windows were carved between the doorways to brighten the interiors.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Each wall of the hall inside is nearly 40 feet (12 m) long and 20 feet (6.1 m) high.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Twelve pillars make a square colonnade inside, supporting the ceiling and creating spacious aisles along the walls.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] There is a shrine carved on the rear wall to house an impressive seated image of the Buddha, his hands being in the ***Dhammacakkappavattana** mudra.* There are four cells on each of the left, rear, and the right walls, though due to rock fault there are none at the ends of the rear aisle.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings of Cave 1 cover the walls and the ceilings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] They are in a fair state of preservation, although the full scheme was never completed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The scenes depicted are mostly didactic, devotional, and ornamental, with scenes from the Jataka stories of the Buddha's former lives as a bodhisattva, the life of the Gautama Buddha, and those of his veneration.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The two most famous individual painted images at Ajanta are the two over-lifesize figures of the protective bodhisattvas Padmapani and Vajrapani on either side of the entrance to the Buddha shrine on the wall of the rear aisle (see illustrations above).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Other significant frescoes in Cave 1 include the Sibi, Sankhapala, Mahajanaka, Mahaummagga, and Champeyya Jataka tales.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave-paintings also show the Temptation of Mara, the miracle of Sravasti where the Buddha simultaneously manifests in many forms, the story of Nanda, and the story of Siddhartha and Yasodhara.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Outside view and main hall with shrine, Cave 2.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 2, adjacent to Cave 1, is known for the paintings that have been preserved on its walls, ceilings, and pillars.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It looks similar to Cave 1 and is in a better state of preservation.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This cave is best known for its feminine focus, intricate rock carvings and paint artwork yet it is incomplete and lacks consistency.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] One of the 5th-century frescos in this cave also shows children at a school, with those in the front rows paying attention to the teacher, while those in the back row are shown distracted and acting.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 2 (35.7 m × 21.6 m) was started in the 460s, but mostly carved between 475 and 477 CE, probably sponsored and influenced by a woman closely related to emperor Harisena.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It has a porch quite different from Cave 1.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Even the façade carvings seem to be different.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave is supported by robust pillars, ornamented with designs.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The front porch consists of cells supported by pillared vestibules on both ends.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The hall has four colonnades which are supporting the ceiling and surrounding a square in the center of the hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Each arm or colonnade of the square is parallel to the respective walls of the hall, making an aisle in between.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The colonnades have rock-beams above and below them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The capitals are carved and painted with various decorative themes that include ornamental, human, animal, vegetative, and semi-divine motifs.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Major carvings include that of goddess Hariti.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] She is a Buddhist deity who originally was the demoness of smallpox and a child eater, who the Buddha converted into a guardian goddess of fertility, easy child birth and one who protects babies.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The paintings on the ceilings and walls of Cave 2 have been widely published.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] They depict the Hamsa, Vidhurapandita, Ruru, Kshanti Jataka tales and the Purna Avadhana.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Other frescos show the miracle of Sravasti, Ashtabhaya Avalokitesvara and the dream of Maya.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Just as the stories illustrated in cave 1 emphasise kingship, those in cave 2 show many noble and powerful women in prominent roles, leading to suggestions that the patron was an unknown woman.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The porch's rear wall has a doorway in the center, which allows entrance to the hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] On either side of the door is a square-shaped window to brighten the interior.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 3 is merely a start of an excavation; according to Spink it was begun right at the end of the final period of work and soon abandoned.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This is an incomplete monastery and only the preliminary excavations of pillared veranda exist.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave was one of the last projects to start at the site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Its date could be ascribed to circa 477 CE, just before the sudden death of Emperor Harisena.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The work stopped after the scooping out of a rough entrance of the hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 4, a Vihara, was sponsored by Mathura, likely not a noble or courtly official, rather a wealthy devotee.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This is the largest vihara in the inaugural group, which suggests he had immense wealth and influence without being a state official.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It is placed at a significantly higher level, possibly because the artists realized that the rock quality at the lower and same level of other caves was poor and they had a better chance of a major vihara at an upper location.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Another likely possibility is that the planners wanted to carve into the rock another large cistern to the left courtside for more residents, mirroring the right, a plan implied by the height of the forward cells on the left side.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The Archaeological Survey of India dates it to the 6th century CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink, in contrast, dates this cave's inauguration a century earlier, to about 463 CE, based on construction style and other inscriptions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 4 shows evidence of a dramatic collapse of its ceiling in the central hall, likely in the 6th century, something caused by the vastness of the cave and geological flaws in the rock.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Later, the artists attempted to overcome this geological flaw by raising the height of the ceiling through deeper excavation of the embedded basalt lava.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a squarish plan, houses a colossal image of the Buddha in preaching pose flanked by bodhisattvas and celestial nymphs hovering above.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists, of a verandah, a hypostylar hall, sanctum with an antechamber and a series of unfinished cells.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This monastery is the largest among the Ajanta caves and it measures nearly 970 square metres (10,400 sq ft) (35 m × 28 m).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The door frame is exquisitely sculpted flanking to the right is carved Bodhisattva as reliever of Eight Great Perils.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The rear wall of the veranda contains the panel of litany of Avalokiteśvara.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave's ceiling collapse likely affected its overall plan, caused it being left incomplete.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Only the Buddha's statue and the major sculptures were completed, and except for what the sponsor considered most important elements all other elements inside the cave were never painted.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 5, an unfinished excavation, was planned as a monastery (10.32 × 16.8 m).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 5 is devoid of sculpture and architectural elements except the door frame.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The ornate carvings on the frame has female figures with mythical *makara* creatures found in ancient and medieval-era Indian arts.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave's construction was likely initiated about 465 CE but abandoned because the rock has geological flaws.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The construction was resumed in 475 CE after Asmakas restarted work at the Ajanta caves, but abandoned again as the artists and sponsor redesigned and focussed on an expanded Cave 6 that abuts Cave 5.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists of a sanctum, a hall on both levels.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The lower level is pillared and has attached cells.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper hall also has subsidiary cells.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The sanctums on both level feature a Buddha in the teaching posture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Elsewhere, the Buddha is shown in different mudras.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The lower level walls depict the Miracle of Sravasti and the Temptation of Mara legends.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Only the lower floor of cave 6 was finished.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The unfinished upper floor of cave 6 has many private votive sculptures, and a shrine Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The lower level of Cave 6 likely was the earliest excavation in the second stage of construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This stage marked the Mahayana theme and Vakataka renaissance period of Ajanta reconstruction that started about four centuries after the earlier Hinayana theme construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper storey was not envisioned in the beginning, it was added as an afterthought, likely around the time when the architects and artists abandoned further work on the geologically flawed rock of Cave 5 immediately next to it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Both lower and upper Cave 6 show crude experimentation and construction errors.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave work was most likely in progress between 460 and 470 CE, and it is the first that shows attendant Bodhisattvas.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper cave construction probably began in 465, progressed swiftly, and much deeper into the rock than the lower level.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The walls and sanctum's door frame of the both levels are intricately carved.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These show themes such as *makaras* and other mythical creatures, apsaras, elephants in different stages of activity, females in waving or welcoming gesture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The upper level of Cave 6 is significant in that it shows a devotee in a kneeling posture at the Buddha's feet, an indication of devotional worship practices by the 5th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The colossal Buddha of the shrine has an elaborate throne back, but was hastily finished in 477/478 CE, when king Harisena died.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The shrine antechamber of the cave features an unfinished sculptural group of the Six Buddhas of the Past, of which only five statues were carved.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This idea may have been influenced from those in Bagh Caves of Madhya Pradesh.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 7 is also a monastery (15.55 × 31.25 m) but a single storey.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists of a sanctum, a hall with octagonal pillars, and eight small rooms for monks.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The sanctum Buddha is shown in preaching posture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] There are many art panels narrating Buddhist themes, including those of the Buddha with Nagamuchalinda and Miracle of Sravasti.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 7 has a grand facade with two porticos.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The veranda has eight pillars of two types.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] One has an octagonal base with amalaka and lotus capital.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The other lacks a distinctly shaped base, features an octagonal shaft instead with a plain capital.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] On the left side in this antechamber are seated or standing sculptures such as those of 25 carved seated Buddhas in various postures and facial expressions, while on the right side are 58 seated Buddha reliefs in different postures, all placed on lotus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] These Buddhas and others on the inner walls of the antechamber are a sculptural depiction of the Miracle of Sravasti in Buddhist theology.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The bottom row shows two *Nagas* (serpents with hoods) holding the blooming lotus stalk.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The antechamber leads to the sanctum through a door frame.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] On this frame are carved two females standing on *makaras* (mythical sea creatures).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Inside the sanctum is the Buddha sitting on a lion throne in cross legged posture, surrounded by other Bodhisattva figures, two attendants with *chauris* (fly-whisks) and flying apsaras above.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Perhaps because of faults in the rock, Cave 7 was never taken very deep into the cliff.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It consists only of the two porticos and a shrine room with antechamber, with no central hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave artwork likely underwent revisions and refurbishments over time.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The first version was complete by about 469 CE, the myriad Buddhas added and painted a few years later between 476 and 478 CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 8 is small, and located at the lowest level in Ajanta, just below the walkway between Caves 7 and 9.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 8 is another unfinished monastery (15.24 × 24.64 m).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] For many decades in the 20th century, this cave was used as a storage and generator room.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It is at the river level with easy access, relatively lower than other caves, and according to Archaeological Survey of India it is possibly one of the earliest monasteries.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Much of its front is damaged, likely from a landslide.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave excavation proved difficult and probably abandoned after a geological fault consisting of a mineral layer proved disruptive to stable carvings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Spink, in contrast, states that Cave 8 is perhaps the earliest cave from the second period, its shrine an "afterthought".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] It may well be the oldest Mahayana monastery excavated in India, according to Spink.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The statue may have been loose rather than carved from the living rock, as it has now vanished.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave was painted, but only traces remain.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Caves 9 and 10 are the two *chaitya* or worship halls from the 2nd to 1st century BCE – the first period of construction, though both were reworked upon the end of the second period of construction in the 5th century CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This has led Spink to the view that Cave 10 was perhaps originally of the 1st century BCE, and cave 9 about a hundred years later.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The small "shrinelets" called caves 9A to 9D and 10A also date from the second period.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Cave 9 arch has remnant profile that suggests that it likely had wooden fittings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The cave has a distinct apsidal shape, nave, aisle and an apse with an icon, architecture, and plan that reminds one of the cathedrals built in Europe many centuries later.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The stupa is at the center of the apse, with a circumambulation path around it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] The stupa sits on a high cylindrical base.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] On the left wall of the cave are votaries approaching the stupa, which suggests a devotional tradition.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] According to Spink, the paintings in this cave, including the intrusive standing Buddhas on the pillars, were added in the 5th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] On the walls are friezes of Jataka tales, but likely from the Hinayana phase of early construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] Some of the panels and reliefs inside as well as outside Cave 10 do not make narrative sense, but are related to Buddhist legends.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This lack of narrative flow may be because these were added by different monks and official donors in the 5th century wherever empty space was available.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p01] This devotionalism and the worship hall character of this cave is the likely reason why four additional shrinelets 9A, 9B, 9C, and 9D were added between Cave 9 and 10.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 10, a vast prayer hall or Chaitya, is dated to about the 1st century BCE, together with the nearby vihara cave No 12.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These two caves are thus among the earliest of the Ajanta complex.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It has a large central apsidal hall with a row of 39 octagonal pillars, a nave separating its aisle and stupa at the end for worship.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The stupa has a *pradakshina patha* (circumambulatory path).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] This cave is significant because its scale confirms the influence of Buddhism in South Asia by the 1st century BCE and its continued though declining influence in India through the 5th century CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Further, the cave includes a number of inscriptions where parts of the cave are "gifts of prasada" by different individuals, which in turn suggests that the cave was sponsored as a community effort rather than a single king or one elite official.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 10 is also historically important because in April 1819, a British Army officer John Smith saw its arch and introduced his discovery to the attention of the Western audience.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Several others caves were also built in Western India around the same period under royal sponsorship.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is thought that the chronology of these early Chaitya Caves is as follows: first Cave 9 at Kondivite Caves and then Cave 12 at the Bhaja Caves, which both predate Cave 10 of Ajanta.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 10 features a Sanskrit inscription in Brahmi script that is archaeologically important.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The inscription is the oldest of the Ajanta site, the Brahmi letters being paleographically dated to circa the 2nd century BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These mostly avoided over-painting the "official" programme and after the best positions were used up are tucked away in less prominent positions not yet painted; the total of these (including those now lost) was probably over 300, and the hands of many different artists are visible.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The paintings are numerous and from two periods, many narrating the Jataka tales in a clockwise sequence.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Both Hinayana and Mahayana stage paintings are discernable, though the former are more faded and begrimed with early centuries of Hinayana worship.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Of interest here is the Saddanta Jataka tale – the fable about six tusked elephant, and the Shyama Jataka – the story about the man who dedicates his life serving his blind parents.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Stella Kramrisch, the oldest layer of the Cave 10 paintings date from about 100 BCE, and the principles behind their composition are analogous to those from the same era at Sanchi and Amaravati.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave veranda has pillars with octagonal shafts and square bases.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The ceiling of the veranda shows evidence of floral designs and eroded reliefs.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Only the center panel is discernible wherein the Buddha is seen with votaries lining up to pray before him.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Inside, the cave consists of a hall with a long rock bench opening into six rooms.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Similar stone benches are found in Nasik Caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Another pillared verandah ends in a sanctum with seated Buddha against an incomplete stupa, and has four cells.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave has a few paintings showing Bodhisattvas and the Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Of these, the Padmapani, a couple gathered to pray, a pair of peafowl, and a female figure painting have survived in the best condition.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The sanctum of this cave may be among the last structures built at Ajanta because it features a circumambulation path around the seated Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Archaeological Survey of India (ASI), Cave 12 is an early stage Hinayana (Theravada) monastery (14.9 × 17.82 m) from the 2nd to 1st century BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Spink however only dates it to the 1st century BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave is damaged with its front wall completely collapsed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Its three sides inside have twelve cells, each with two stone beds.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 13 is another small monastery from the early period, consisting of a hall with seven cells, each also with two stone beds, all carved out of the rock.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Each cell has rock-cut beds for the monks.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In contrast to ASI's estimate, Gupte and Mahajan date both these caves about two to three centuries later, between 1st and 2nd-century CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 14 is another unfinished monastery (13.43 × 19.28 m) but carved above Cave 13.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The entrance door frame shows *sala bhanjikas*.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 15 is a more complete monastery (19.62 × 15.98 m) with evidence that it had paintings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave consists of an eight-celled hall ending in a sanctum, an antechamber and a verandah with pillars.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The reliefs show the Buddha, while the sanctum Buddha is shown seated in the Simhasana posture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 15 door frame has carvings of pigeons eating grain.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 15A is the smallest cave with a hall and one cell on each side.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Its entrance is just to the right of the elephant-decorated entrance to Cave 16.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is an ancient Hinayana cave with three cells opening around a minuscule central hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The doors are decorated with a rail and arch pattern.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It had an inscription in an ancient script, which has been lost.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Entrance stairs to the single-storey Cave 16, with stone elephants and front with pillars (left).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Inside hall with seated Buddha statue (right).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 16 occupies a prime position near the middle of site, and was sponsored by Varahadeva, minister of Vakataka king Harishena (r. c.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] He was, states Spink, probably someone who revered both the Buddha and the Hindu gods, as he proclaims his Hindu heritage in an inscription in the nearby Ghatotkacha Cave.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The 7th-century Chinese traveler Xuan Zang described the cave as the entrance to the site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 16 (19.5 m × 22.25 m × 4.6 m) influenced the architecture of the entire site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Spink and other scholars call it the "crucial cave" that helps trace the chronology of the second and closing stages of the entire cave's complex construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 16 is a Mahayana monastery and has the standard arrangement of a main doorway, two windows, and two aisle doorways.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The veranda of this monastery is 19.5 m × 3 m, while the main hall is almost a perfect square with 19.5 m side.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Narratives include various Jataka tales such as Hasti, Mahaummagga and the Sutasoma fables.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Other frescos depict the conversion of Nanda, miracle of Sravasti, Sujata's offering, Asita's visit, the dream of Maya, the Trapusha and Bhallika story, and the ploughing festival.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The Hasti Jataka frescos tell the story of a Bodhisattva elephant who learns of a large group of people starving, then tells them to go below a cliff where they could find food.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The elephant proceeds to sacrifice himself by jumping off that cliff thereby becoming food so that the people can survive.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These frescos are found immediately to the left of entrance, in the front corridor and the narrative follows a clockwise direction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The Mahaummagga Jataka frescos are found on the left wall of the corridor, which narrates the story of a child Bodhisattva.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Thereafter, in the left corridor is the legend surrounding the conversion of Nanda – the half brother of the Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The story depicted is one of the two major versions of the Nanda legend in the Buddhist tradition, one where Nanda wants to lead a sensuous life with the girl he had just wed and the Buddha takes him to heaven and later hell to show the spiritual dangers of a sensual life.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] After the Nanda-related frescos, the cave presents Manushi Buddhas, followed by flying votaries with offerings to worship the Buddha and the Buddha seated in teaching asana and *dharma chakra mudra*.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The right wall of the corridor show the scenes from the life of the Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These include Sujata offering food to the Buddha with a begging bowl in white dress, Tapussa and Bhalluka next to the Buddha after they offering wheat and honey to the Buddha as monk, the future Buddha sitting alone under a tree, and the Buddha at a ploughing festival.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] One mural shows Buddha's parents trying to dissuade him from becoming a monk.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Another shows the Buddha at the palace surrounded by men in *dhoti* and women in *sari* as his behavior presents the four signs that he is likely to renounce.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] On this side of the corridor are also paintings that show the future Buddha as a baby with sage Asita with rishi-like looks.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Spink, some of the Cave 16 paintings were left incomplete.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 17 (34.5 m × 25.63 m) along with Cave 16 with two great stone elephants at the entrance and Cave 26 with sleeping Buddha, were some of the many caves sponsored by the Hindu Vakataka prime minister Varahadeva.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 17 had additional donors such as the local king Upendragupta, as evidenced by the inscription therein.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave features a large and most sophisticated vihara design, along with some of the best-preserved and well-known paintings of all the caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] While Cave 16 is known for depicting the life stories of the Buddha, the Cave 17 paintings has attracted much attention for extolling human virtues by narrating the Jataka tales.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The narration includes attention to details and a realism which Stella Kramrisch calls "lavish elegance" accomplished by efficient craftsmen.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The ancient artists, states Kramrisch, tried to show wind passing over a crop by showing it bending in waves, and a similar profusion of rhythmic sequences that unroll story after story, visually presenting the metaphysical.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The Cave 17 monastery includes a colonnaded porch, a number of pillars each with a distinct style, a peristyle design for the interior hall, a shrine antechamber located deep in the cave, larger windows and doors for more light, along with extensive integrated carvings of Indian gods and goddesses.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The hall of this monastery is a 380.53 square metres (4,096.0 sq ft) square, with 20 pillars.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The grand scale of the carving also introduced errors of taking out too much rock to shape the walls, states Spink, which led to the cave being splayed out toward the rear.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 17 has one long inscription by king Upendragupta, in which he explains that he has "expended abundant wealth" on building this vihara, bringing much satisfaction to the devotees.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Altogether, Upendragupta is known to have sponsored at least 5 of the caves in Ajanta.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] He may have spent too much wealth on religious pursuits however, as he was ultimately defeated by the attacks of the Asmaka.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The paintings of Cave 17 depict Buddha in various forms and postures – Vipasyi, Sikhi, Visvbhu, Krakuchchanda, Kanakamuni, Kashyapa and Sakyamuni.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Also depicted are Avalokitesvara, the story of Udayin and Gupta, the story of Nalagiri, the Wheel of life, a panel celebrating various ancient Indian musicians and a panel that tells the tales of Prince Simhala's expedition to Sri Lanka.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The narrative frescos depict the various Jataka tales such as the Shaddanta, Hasti, Hamsa, Vessantara, Sutasoma, Mahakapi (in two versions), Sarabhamiga, Machchha, Matiposaka, Shyama, Mahisha, Valahassa, Sibi, Ruru and Nigrodamiga Jatakas.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The depictions weave in the norms of the early 1st millennium culture and the society.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] They show themes as diverse as a shipwreck, a princess applying makeup, lovers in scenes of dalliance, and a wine drinking scene of a couple with the woman and man amorously seated.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Some frescos attempt to show the key characters from various parts of a Jataka tale by co-depicting animals and attendants in the same scene.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 18 is a small rectangular space (3.38 × 11.66 m) with two octagonal pillars and it joins another cell.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Entrance façade and inside worship hall, Cave 19, sponsored by king Upendragupta.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 is a worship hall (chaitya griha, 16.05 × 7.09 m) datable to the fifth century CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The hall shows painted Buddha, depicted in different postures.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] This worship hall is now visited through what was previously a carved room.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The presence of this room before the hall suggests that the original plan included a mandala style courtyard for devotees to gather and wait, an entrance and facade to this courtyard, all of whose ruins are now lost to history.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 is one of the caves known for its sculpture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It includes Naga figures with a serpent canopy protecting the Buddha, similar to those found for spiritual icons in the ancient Jain and Hindu traditions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It includes Yaksha dwarapala (guardian) images on the side of its vetayana (arches), flying couples, sitting Buddha, standing Buddhas and evidence that its ceiling was once painted.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 drew upon on the plan and experimentation in Cave 9.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 19 excavation and stupa was likely in place by 467 CE, and its finishing and artistic work continued into the early 470s, but it too was an incomplete cave when it was dedicated in 471 CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The entrance facade of the Cave 19 worship hall is ornate.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Two round pillars with fluted floral patterns and carved garlands support a porch.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Its capital is an inverted lotus connecting to an *amalaka*.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] To its left is standing Buddha in *varada hasta mudra* with a devotee prostrating at his feet.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] On right is a relief of woman with one hand holding a pitcher and other touching her chin.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Above is a seated Buddha in meditating mudra.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Towards the right of the entrance is the "Mother and Child" sculpture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A figure with begging bowl is the Buddha, watching him are his wife and son.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The worship hall is apsidal, with 15 pillars dividing it into two side aisles and one nave.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The round pillars have floral reliefs and a fluted shaft topped with Buddha in its capitals.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Next, to the Buddha in the capitals are elephants, horses and flying apsara friezes found elsewhere in India, reflecting the style of the Gupta Empire artwork.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Sharma, the similarities at the Karla Caves Great Chaitya, built in the 2nd century CE, suggest that Cave 19 may have been modeled after it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The walls and the ceiling of the side aisles inside the worship hall are covered with paintings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These show the Buddha, flowers, and in the left aisle the "Mother and Child" legend again.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 20 is a monastery hall (16.2 × 17.91 m) from the 5th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Its construction, states Spink, was started in the 460s by king Upendragupta, with his expressed desire "to make the great tree of religious merit grow".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The work on Cave 20 was pursued in parallel with other caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 20 has exquisite detailing, states Spink, but it was relatively lower on priority than Caves 17 and 19.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The work on Cave 20 was intermittently stopped and then continued in the following decade.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The vihara consists of a sanctum, four cells for monks and a pillared verandah with two stone cut windows for light.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Prior to entering the main hall, on the left of veranda are two Buddhas carved above the window and side cell.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The ceiling of the main hall has remnants of painting.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The sanctum Buddha is in preaching posture.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave is known for the sculpture showing seven Buddhas with attendants on its lintel.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave has a dedicatory Sanskrit inscription in Brahmi script in its verandah, and it calls the cave as a *mandapa*.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of the figural and ornamental carvings in Cave 20 are similar to Cave 19, and to a lesser degree to those found in Cave 17.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] This may be because the same architects and artisans were responsible for the evolution of the three caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The door frames in Cave 20 are quasi-structural, something unique at the Ajanta site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The decorations are also innovative in Cave 20, such as one showing the Buddha seated against two pillows and "a richly laden mango tree behind him", states Spink.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 21 is a hall (29.56 × 28.03 m) with twelve rock-cut rooms for monks, a sanctum, and twelve pillared and pilastered verandah.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The carvings on the pilaster include those of animals and flowers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The pillars feature reliefs of apsaras, Nagaraja, and Nagarani, as well as devotees bowing with the Anjali mudra.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The hall shows evidence that it used to be completely painted.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 22 is a small vihara (12.72 × 11.58 m) with a narrow veranda and four unfinished cells.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is excavated at a higher level and has to be reached by a flight of steps.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Inside, the Buddha is seated in pralamba-padasana.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The painted figures in Cave 22 show Manushi-Buddhas with Maitreya.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A pilaster on the left side of the Cave 22 veranda has a Sanskrit prose inscription.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is damaged in parts, and the legible parts state that this is a "meritorious gift of a mandapa by Jayata", calling Jayata's family as "a great Upasaka", and ending the inscription with "may the merit of this be for excellent knowledge to all sentient beings, beginning with father and mother".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 23 is also unfinished, consisting of a hall (28.32 × 22.52 m) but a design similar to Cave 21.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave differs in its pillar decorations and the naga doorkeepers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Exterior, and unfinished inside of Cave 24.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 24 is like Cave 21, unfinished but much larger.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It features the second largest monastery hall (29.3 × 29.3 m) after Cave 4.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave 24 monastery has been important to scholarly studies of the site because it shows how multiple crews of workers completed their objectives in parallel.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cell construction began as soon as the aisle had been excavated and while the main hall and sanctum were under construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The construction of Cave 24 was planned in 467 CE, but likely started in 475 CE, with support from Buddhabhadra, then abruptly ended in 477 with the sponsor king Harisena's death.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is significant in having one of the most complex capitals on a pillar at the Ajanta site, an indication of how the artists excelled and continuously improved their sophistication as they worked with the rock inside the cave.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The artists carved fourteen complex miniature figures on the central panel of the right center porch pillar, while working in dim light in a cramped cave space.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The medallion reliefs in Cave 24 similarly show loving couples and anthropomorphic arts, rather than flowers of earlier construction.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 24's sanctum has a seated Buddha in pralamba-padasana.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Its hall (11.37 × 12.24 m) is similar to other monasteries, but has no sanctum, includes an enclosed courtyard and is excavated at an upper level.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 26 is a worship hall (chaityagriha, 25.34 × 11.52 m) similar in plan to Cave 19.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is much larger and with elements of a vihara design.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] An inscription states that a monk Buddhabhadra and his friend minister serving king of Asmaka gifted this vast cave.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The inscription includes a vision statement and the aim to make "a memorial on the mountain that will endure for as long as the moon and the sun continue", translates Walter Spink.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is likely that the builders focussed on sculpture, rather than paintings, in Cave 26 because they believed stone sculpture will far more endure than paintings on the wall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The sculptures in Cave 26 are elaborate and more intricate.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is among the last caves excavated, and an inscription suggests late 5th or early 6th century according to ASI.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave consists of an apsidal hall with side aisles for circumambulation (*pradikshana*).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] This path is full of carved Buddhist legends, three depictions of the Miracle of Sravasti in the right ambulatory side of the aisle, and seated Buddhas in various mudra.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of these were added later by devotees, and therefore are intrusive to the aims of the original planners.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The artwork begins on the wall of the aisle, immediately the left side of entrance.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The major artworks include the Mahaparinirvana of Buddha (reclining Buddha) on the wall, followed by the legend called the "Temptations by Mara".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The temptations include the seduction by Mara's daughters who are depicted below the meditating Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] They are shown scantly dressed and in seductive postures, while on both the left and right side of the Buddha are armies of Mara attempting to distract him with noise and threaten him with violence.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In the top right corner is the image of a dejected Mara frustrated by his failure to disturb the resolve or focus of the ascetic Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] At the center of the apse is a rock-cut stupa.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The stupa has an image of the Buddha on its front, 18 panels on its base, 18 panels above these, a three tiered *torana* above him, and apsaras are carved on the *anda* (hemispherical egg) stupa.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] On top of the dagoba is a nine-tiered *harmika*, a symbolism for the nine saṃsāra (Buddhism) heavens in Mahayana cosmology.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The walls, pillars, brackets and the triforium are extensively carved with Buddhist themes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of the wall reliefs and images in this cave were badly damaged, and have been restored as a part of the site conservation efforts.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Between cave 26 and its left wing, there is an inscription by a courtier of Rashtrakuta Nanaraj (who is mentioned in the Multai and Sangaloda plates), from late 7th or early 8th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 27 is a monastery and may have been planned as an attachment to Cave 26.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Its two storeys are damaged, with the upper level partially collapsed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Its plan is similar to other monasteries.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] : Cave 28, further beyond Cave 27, at the westernmost end of the Ajanta complex.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] : Cave 29, high up between caves 20 and 21.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 28 is an unfinished monastery, partially excavated, at the westernmost end of the Ajanta complex and barely accessible.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 29 an unfinished monastery at the highest level of the Ajanta complex, apparently unnoticed when the initial numbering system was established, and physically located between Caves 20 and 21.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In 1956, a landslide covered the footpath leading to Cave 16.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In the attempts to clear and restore the walkway, a small aperture and votive stupa were noticed in the debris by the workers, in a location near the stream bed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Further tracing and excavations led to a previously unknown Hinayana monastery cave dated to the 2nd and 1st century BCE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 30 may actually be the oldest cave of the Ajanta complex.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It is a 3.66 m × 3.66 m cave with three cells, each with two stone beds and stone pillows on the side of each cell.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cell door lintels show lotus and garland carvings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The cave has two inscriptions in an unknown script.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It also has a platform on its veranda with a fine view of the river ravine below and the forest cover.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Gupte and Mahajan, this cave may have been closed at some point with large carefully carved pieces as it distracted the entrance view of Cave 16.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Over 80% of the Ajanta caves were *vihara* (temporary traveler residences, monasteries).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The designers and artisans who built these caves included facilities for collecting donations and storing grains and food for the visitors and monks.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Many of the caves include large repositories cut into the floor.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The largest storage spaces are found, states Spink, in the "very commodious recesses in the shrines of both Ajanta Cave Lower 6 and Cave 11".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These caves were probably chosen because of their relative convenience and the security they offered due to their higher level.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The choice of integrating covered vaults cut into the floor may have been driven by the need to provide sleeping space.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A burnt-brick vihara monastery facing the caves on the right bank of the river Waghora has been recently excavated.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It has a number of cells facing a central courtyard, in which a stupa was established.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A coin of the Western Satraps ruler Visvasena (ruled 293–304 CE) as well as a gold coin of the Byzantine Emperor Theodosius II (ruled 402-450 CE) were found in the excavations, giving further numismatic confirmation for the dating of the caves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A terracotta plaque of Mahishasuramardini was also found, which was possibly under worship by the artisans.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The paintings have deteriorated significantly since they were rediscovered, and a number of 19th-century copies and drawings are important for a complete understanding of the works.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A number of attempts to copy the Ajanta paintings began in the 19th century for European and Japanese museums.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Some of these works have later been lost in natural and fire disasters.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In 1846 for example, Major Robert Gill, an Army officer from Madras Presidency and a painter, was appointed by the Royal Asiatic Society to make copies of the frescos on the cave walls.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Gill worked on his painting at the site from 1844 to 1863.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] He made 27 copies of large sections of murals, but all but four were destroyed in a fire at the Crystal Palace in London in 1866, where they were on display.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Gill returned to the site, and recommenced his labours, replicating the murals until his death in 1875.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Another attempt was made in 1872 when the Bombay Presidency commissioned John Griffiths to work with his students to make copies of Ajanta paintings, again for shipping to England.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] They worked on this for thirteen years and some 300 canvases were produced, many of which were displayed at the Imperial Institute on Exhibition Road in London, one of the forerunners of the Victoria and Albert Museum.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] But in 1885 another fire destroyed over a hundred of the paintings in storage in a wing of the museum.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The V&A still has 166 paintings surviving from both sets, though none have been on permanent display since 1955.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The largest are some 3 by 6 metres (9.8 ft × 19.7 ft).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A conservation project was undertaken on about half of them in 2006, also involving the University of Northumbria.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Griffith and his students had painted many of the paintings with "cheap varnish" in order to make them easier to see, which has added to the deterioration of the originals, as has, according to Spink and others, recent cleaning by the ASI.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A further set of copies was made between 1909 and 1911 by Christiana Herringham (Lady Herringham) and a group of students from the Calcutta School of Art that included the future Indian Modernist painter Nandalal Bose.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The copies were published in full colour as the first publication of London's fledgling India Society.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] More than the earlier copies, these aimed to fill in holes and damage to recreate the original condition rather than record the state of the paintings as she was seeing them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to one writer, unlike the paintings created by her predecessors Griffiths and Gill, whose copies were influenced by British Victorian styles of painting, those of the Herringham expedition preferred an 'Indian Renascence' aesthetic of the type pioneered by Abanindranath Tagore.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Early photographic surveys were made by Robert Gill, whose photos, including some using stereoscopy, were used in books by him and Fergusson (many are available online from the British Library), then Victor Goloubew in 1911 and E.L.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Vassey, who took the photos in the four volume study of the caves by Ghulam Yazdani (published 1930–1955).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Some slightly creative copies of Ajanta frescos, especially the painting of the Adoration of the Buddha from the shrine antechamber of Cave 17, were commissioned by Thomas Holbein Hendley (1847–1917) for the decoration of the walls of the hall of the Albert Hall Museum, Jaipur, India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] He had the work painted by a local artist variously named Murli or Murali.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The museum was opened to the public in 1887.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] This work is otherwise presented as characteristic of the end of the 19th century.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Another attempt to make copies of the murals was made by the Japanese artist Arai Kampō (荒井寛方:1878–1945) after being invited by Rabindranath Tagore to India to teach Japanese painting techniques.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] He worked on making copies with tracings on Japanese paper from 1916 to 1918 and his work was conserved at Tokyo Imperial University until the materials perished during the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] heading to a temple, five women chatting in a market square, children playing a board game near a banana tree.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta cave arts are a window into the culture, society and religiosity of the native population of India between the 2nd century BCE and 5th century CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Different scholars have variously interpreted them from the perspective of gender studies, history, sociology, and the anthropology of South Asia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The dress, the jewellery, the gender relations, the social activities depicted show at least the lifestyle of the royalty and elite, and in others definitely the costumes of the common man, monks and rishi.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] They shine "light on life in India" around mid 1st millennium CE.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta paintings provide a contrast between the spiritual life of monks who had given up all materialistic possessions versus the sensual life of those it considered materialistic, luxurious, symbols of wealth, leisurely and high fashion.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Many frescos show scenes from shops, festivals, jesters at processions, palaces and performance art pavilions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These friezes share themes and details of those found in Bharhut, Sanchi, Amaravati, Ellora, Bagh, Aihole, Badami and other archaeological sites in India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Ajanta caves contributes to visual and descriptive sense of the ancient and early medieval Indian culture and artistic traditions, particularly those around the Gupta Empire era period.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The earliest colonial era descriptions of the Ajanta caves was largely orientalist and critical.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to William Dalrymple, the subjects in the Ajanta caves were puzzling to 19th-century Orientalists.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Lacking the Asian cultural heritage and with no knowledge of Jataka Tales or equivalent Indian fables, they could not comprehend it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] They projected their own views and assumptions, calling it something that lacks reason and rationale, something that is a meaningless crude representation of royalty and foreigners with mysticism and sensuousness.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The 19th-century views and interpretations of the Ajanta Caves were conditioned by ideas and assumptions in the colonial mind, saw what they wanted to see.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] To many who are unaware of the premises of Indian religions in general, and Buddhism in particular, the significance of Ajanta Caves has been like the rest of Indian art.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Richard Cohen, the Ajanta Caves to them has been yet another example of "worship this stock, or that stone, or monstrous idol".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In contrast, to the Indian mind and the larger Buddhist community, it is everything that art ought to be, the religious and the secular, the spiritual and the social fused to enlightened perfection.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Walter Spink – one of the most respected Art historians on Ajanta, these caves were by 475 CE a much-revered site to the Indians, with throngs of "travelers, pilgrims, monks and traders".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The site was vastly transformed into its current form in just 20 years, between early 460 CE to early 480 CE, by regional architects and artisans.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] This accomplishment, states Spink, makes Ajanta, "one of the most remarkable creative achievements in man's history".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta Caves painting are a significant source of socio-economic information in ancient India, particularly in relation to the interactions of India with foreign cultures at the time most of the paintings were made, in the 5th century CE (Common Era).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Indian historian Haroon Khan Sherwani: "The paintings at Ajanta clearly demonstrate the cosmopolitan character of Buddhism, which opened its way to men of all races, Greek, Persian, Saka, Pahlava, Kushan and Huna".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Depictions of foreigners abound: according to Spink, "Ajanta's paintings are filled with such foreign types." They have sometimes been a source of misinterpretation as in the so-called "Persian Embassy Scene".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These foreigners may reflect the Sassanian merchants, visitors and the flourishing trade routes of the day.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 1, for example, shows a mural fresco with characters with foreigner faces or dresses, the so-called "Persian Embassy Scene".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] This scene is located at the right of the entrance door upon entering the hall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Spink, James Fergusson, a 19th-century architectural historian, had decided that this scene corresponded to the Persian ambassador in 625 CE to the court of the Hindu Chalukya king Pulakeshin II.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] An alternate theory has been that the fresco represents a Hindu ambassador visiting the Persian king Khusrau II in 625 CE, a theory that Fergusson disagreed with.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Cave 1 has several frescos with characters with foreigners' faces or dresses.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Similar depictions are found in the paintings of Cave 17.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Such murals, states Pia Brancaccio, suggest a prosperous and multicultural society in 5th-century India active in international trade.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These also suggest that this trade was economically important enough to the Deccan region that the artists chose to include it with precision.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Additional evidence of international trade includes the use of the blue lapis lazuli pigment to depict foreigners in the Ajanta paintings, which must have been imported from Afghanistan or Iran.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] It also suggests, states Brancaccio, that the Buddhist monastic world was closely connected with trading guilds and the court culture in this period.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] A small number of scenes show foreigners drinking wine in Caves 1 and 2.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Some show foreign Near East kings with wine and their retinue which presumably add to the "general regal emphasis" of the cave.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] According to Brancaccio, the Ajanta paintings show a variety of colorful, delicate textiles and women making cotton.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Textile probably was one of the major exports to foreign lands, along with gems.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These were exported first through the Red Sea, and later through the Persian Gulf, thereby bringing a period of economic and cultural exchange between the Indians, the Sasanian Empire and the Persian merchants before Islam was founded in the Arabian peninsula.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] While scholars generally agree that these murals confirm trade and cultural connections between India and Sassanian west, their specific significance and interpretation varies.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Brancaccio, for example, suggests that the ship and jars in them probably reflect foreign ships carrying wine imported to India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In contrast, Schlinghoff interprets the jars to be holding water, and ships shown as Indian ships used in international trade.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Similar depictions are found in the paintings of Cave 17, but this time in direct relation to the worship of the Buddha.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In Cave 17, a painting of the Buddha descending from the Trayastrimsa Heaven shows he being attended by many foreigners.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Many foreigners in this painting are thus shown as listeners to the Buddhist Dharma.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The ethnic diversity is depicted in the painting in the clothes (kaftans, Sasanian helmets, round caps), hairdos and skin colors.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In the Visvantara Jataka of Cave 17, according to Brancaccio, the scene probably shows a servant from Central Asia holding a foreign metal ewer, while a dark-complexioned servant holds a cup to an amorous couple.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] In another painting in Cave 17, relating to the conversion of Nanda, a man possibly from northeast Africa appears as a servant.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] These representations show, states Brancaccio, that the artists were familiar with people of Sogdia, Central Asia, Persia and possibly East Africa.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Another hypothesis is offered by Upadhya, who states that the artists who built Ajanta caves "very probably included foreigners".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The Ajanta paintings, or more likely the general style they come from, influenced painting in Tibet and Sri Lanka.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Some influences from Ajanta have also suggested in the Kizil Caves of the Tarim Basin, in particular in early caves such as the *Peacock Cave*.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] The rediscovery of ancient Indian paintings at Ajanta provided Indian artists with examples from ancient India to follow.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Nandalal Bose experimented with techniques to follow the ancient style which allowed him to develop his unique style.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Abanindranath Tagore and Syed Thajudeen also used the Ajanta paintings for inspiration.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Anna Pavlova's ballet *Ajanta's Frescoes* was inspired by her visit to Ajanta, choreographed by Ivan Clustine, with music by Nikolai Tcherepnin (one report says Mikhail Fokine in 1923). and premiered at Covent Garden in 1923.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Jewish American poet Muriel Rukeyser wrote about the caves in "Ajanta," the opening poem of her third collection *Beast in View* (1944).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/ajanta-caves-p02] Rukeyser was inspired in part by writings on the caves by artist Mukul Dey in 1925 and art historian Stella Kramrisch in 1937.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The settlement was destroyed during the Theran eruption sometime in the 16th century BC, and was buried in volcanic ash, which helped preserve its fine frescoes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Akrotiri has been excavated since 1967, after earlier excavations on the island.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The earliest evidence for human habitation of Akrotiri can be traced back as early as the fifth millennium BCE when it was a small fishing and farming village.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] By the end of the third millennium, this community developed and expanded significantly.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] One factor for Akrotiri's growth may be the trade relations it established with other cultures in the Aegean, as evidenced in fragments of foreign pottery at the site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Akrotiri's strategic position on the primary sailing route between Cyprus and Minoan Crete also made it an important point for the copper trade, thus allowing it to become an important centre for processing copper, as proven by the discovery of moulds and crucibles there.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Akrotiri's prosperity continued for about another 500 years; paved streets, an extensive drainage system, the production of high-quality pottery and further craft specialization all point to the level of sophistication achieved by the settlement.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] This all came to an end, however, in the 16th century BCE with the volcanic eruption of Thera.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] There is a variety of dating evidence for the eruption, but its exact year is not known.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Radiocarbon dating places it most probably between 1620 and 1530 BCE, which is also in accord with the date range of 1570 to 1500 BCE suggested by similarities of the material culture with other sites in the Aegean.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Unusual growth patterns observed in tree rings in 1597, 1560, 1546 and 1544 BCE are consistent with a major volcanic event in any of those years.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The latter three dates might be the best candidates as they are also considered possible for Egyptian New Kingdom records that are thought to refer to the eruption.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Akrotiri was buried by the massive Theran eruption in the middle of the second millennium BCE (during the Late Minoan IA period); as a result, like the Roman ruins of Pompeii after it, it is remarkably well-preserved.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Frescoes, pottery, furniture, advanced drainage systems and three-story buildings have been discovered at the site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Despite being a Cycladic settlement, the site is associated with the Minoan civilization due to inscriptions in Linear A, and close similarities in artifact and fresco styles.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The earliest excavations on the island of Santorini were conducted by French geologist F.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Fouque in 1867 after some local people found old artifacts at a quarry.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Later, in 1895–1900, the digs by German archeologist Baron Friedrich Hiller von Gaertringen revealed the ruins of ancient Thera on Mesa Vouno, which date from the archaic period, much after the Minoan eruption.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Zahn excavated in the locality of Potamos, near Akrotiri, under the auspices of the German Archaeological Institute at Athens.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The extensive modern excavation was started in 1967 by Spyridon Marinatos and revealed the full value of this site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Marinatos's choice of the site proved to be correct and a few hours into the excavation, the remains of the buried city began to be discovered.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The next step was to determine the extent of the city, which took two seasons devoted to the site in 1967 and 1968.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In the early years of the excavation, a great deal of attention was paid towards the organization of proper facilities for the dig, including substantial workshops, laboratories built for storage, repair, and treatment, and areas for examination of archaeological finds.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Because of the site being preserved in thick, volcanic debris, Marinatos noted that many of the buildings were preserved to a height of more than a single storey, creating unique challenges for excavation.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] He experimented with tunnelling into the pumice, but this technique was later abandoned.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In 1975, after Marinatos' death, Christos Doumas took over as the head of excavations.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Excavated artifacts have been installed in a museum distant from the site (Museum of Prehistoric Thera), with many objects and artworks presented.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Only a single gold object has been found, hidden beneath flooring, and no uninterred human skeletal remains have been found.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] This indicates that an orderly evacuation was performed with little or no loss of life.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In 2005, a new roof structure, meant to protect the site, collapsed just before its completion, killing one visitor.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] No damage was caused to the antiquities.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Between 2005 and April 2012, the site was closed to visitors.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Between 2005 and 2016, excavations stopped, due to lack of funding, then resumed with sponsor support.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In October 2018, a small shrine with a marble figurine of a woman was discovered in the "House of the Thrania" which is located near Xeste 3, where a golden goat was found in 1999.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The frescoes in Akrotiri are especially important for the study of Minoan art because they are much better preserved than those that were already known from Knossos and other sites on Crete, which have nearly all survived only in small fragments, usually fallen to the ground.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] All of the pigments used by the artists at Akrotiri for painting the frescoes look as though they are mineral based and thus have resulted in the great preservation of the pieces.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The colors used in Theran painting include white, yellow, red, brown, blue and black.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The technique used is not true fresco, except for a few isolated instances, and instead appears as though the painting was begun while the plaster was still wet, but as though the artist made no effort to keep it wet, and seemed content to complete the work on a dry surface.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] As a result, often on the same fresco, the paint has penetrated the plaster in some areas but flakes off easily in others.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Specialized techniques were required when it was discovered early on in the excavation process that the site contained numerous well preserved fresco wall paintings.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Tassos Margaritoff, one of the leading restorers of Byzantine frescoes, is currently the supervisor of the Akrotiri project.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The first fragments of fresco were discovered in 1968 in Sector Alpha and depict the head of an African, the head of a blue monkey and some large flying blue birds.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In 1969, the fresco of the Blue Monkeys in Room Beta 6 was discovered and created increased excitement at the site.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The rocky landscape which the monkeys are depicted climbing upon mimics the similar volcanic rocks near the site presently.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In 1970 the Spring Fresco was uncovered in Room Delta 2.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] It is the first fresco to have been found perfectly preserved and still standing in its original installed position.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The supporting wall of the fresco was not in the best condition and thus the fresco had to be removed immediately in order to preserve it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Rescuing the fresco was a delicate procedure and allowed the archaeologists and restorers to develop invaluable experience.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] A few other frescoes including The Fisherman and the Lady from the House of Ladies have been found standing, though detached from the wall.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The excavations at Akrotiri have produced a large variety of artifacts revealing numerous varieties of Late Cycladic (LC I) pottery from the area.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Pottery is the most common and most enduring commodity in the culture of the majority of ancient societies and, thus, is of great importance to archaeologists in interpreting Ancient Greek societies.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] At Akrotiri, pottery is particularly abundant because of the circumstances surrounding the demise of the town, in that its sudden evacuation meant that inhabitants were only able to take their most valuable possessions with them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Serving a multitude of purposes, pottery can tell a great deal about the society in which it were produced.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Large jars were used as containers for storage of goods, while others like stirrup jars were designed for the transportation of certain commodities.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] As well, there were also vessels for preparing and cooking food, for eating and drinking and many other diverse activities, including bathtubs, braziers, oil lamps, bee-hives, flower pots, etc.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Most evidently, the shape, size and perhaps even the decoration of the vases were closely related to their use in the ancient world.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In regards to furniture, the volcanic ash which engulfed the city often penetrated into the houses in large quantities and, in these layers of fine volcanic dust, produced negatives of the disintegrated wooden objects.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Using these negatives as molds, liquid plaster-of-Paris can be poured in and produce casts of parts, or even entire pieces of furniture such as beds, tables, chairs or stools.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] Offering tables are one of the most common finds in Akrotiri and were either made of clay or coated with plaster, decorated in the same technique as the wall paintings, and only consisted of three highly decorated legs and a top.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] In the 'House of the Benches' a large deposit of between 300 and 500 horns were found.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The horns were from cattle, sheep and goats and almost all of them were altered by fire, with keratinous sheath removed and painted with patterns in ochre.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] There is a path descending from the first houses of the modern settlement to the parking lot of the excavations of Akrotiri, connecting the old excavation site to the town of Akrotiri.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The path was signposted and reopened in September 2012 and now regularly undergoes maintenance, thanks to international volunteers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The local population has been the first supporter of this initiative and in charge of the upkeep of the path, working alongside the volunteers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/akrotiri-prehistoric-city] The path is suitable for mountain biking, hiking and many other activities.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Born in Pella, Macedon, Alexander was tutored by philosopher and polymath Aristotle until the age of 16.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In 335 BC, shortly after assuming the throne of Macedon, he launched a campaign in the Balkans and reasserted control over Thrace and parts of Illyria before marching on the city of Thebes, which was subsequently destroyed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then assumed leadership of the League of Corinth, created by his father.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] With this authority over all Greeks he launched a pan-Hellenic invasion of the Persian Achaemenid Empire in 334 BC, and with it began a series of campaigns which lasted for ten years.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Following his conquest of Asia Minor and a series of decisive battles, particularly at Issus and Gaugamela, the power of the Achaemenid Empire was broken.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He subsequently overthrew Darius III and conquered the Achaemenid Empire in its entirety.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After the fall of Persia, the Macedonian Empire held a vast swath of territory between the Adriatic Sea and the Indus River.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander endeavored to reach the "ends of the world and the Great Outer Sea" and invaded India in 326 BC, achieving an important victory over Porus, an ancient Indian king of present-day Punjab, at the Battle of the Hydaspes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Facing mutiny from troops, he was eventually forced to turn back at the Beas River, and later died in 323 BC in Babylon, Mesopotamia, the city which he had planned to make the capital of his empire, while on his return to Greece.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death put an end to his planned invasion of Arabia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the years following his death, a series of civil wars broke out across the Macedonian Empire, eventually leading to its disintegration at the hands of the Diadochi.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death marks the conventional beginning of the Hellenistic period.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Through his conquests, he built a legacy that includes the cultural diffusion and syncretism, which gave rise to Greco-Buddhism and Hellenistic Judaism.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He founded more than twenty cities, with the most prominent being the city of Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's establishment of Greek colonies and the spreading of Greek culture led to Hellenistic civilization becoming a major force in the ancient world, influencing regions as far east as the Indian subcontinent.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Hellenistic period developed through the Roman Empire into modern Western culture; the Greek language became the *lingua franca* of the region and was the predominant language of the Byzantine Empire until its collapse in 1453 AD.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander became a legendary hero similar to Achilles, featuring prominently in the historical and mythical traditions of both Greek and non-Greek cultures.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] His military achievements and successes in battle made him the touchstone against which many later military leaders would judge themselves.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] His tactics remain a significant subject of study in military academies worldwide.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Legends of Alexander's exploits were coalesced into the 3rd century *Alexander Romance* which, in the premodern period, went through over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations and was translated into almost every European vernacular and every language of the Islamic world.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After the Bible, it was the most popular form of European literature.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander III was born in Pella, the capital of the Kingdom of Macedon, on the sixth day of the ancient Greek month of Hekatombaion, which probably corresponds to 20 July 356 BC (although the exact date is uncertain).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He was the son of the king of Macedon, Philip II of the Argead dynasty and his fourth wife, Olympias (daughter of Neoptolemus I, Aeacid king of Epirus).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Although Philip had seven or eight wives, Olympias was his principal wife for some time, likely because she gave birth to Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Several legends surround Alexander's birth and childhood.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient Greek biographer Plutarch, on the eve of the consummation of her marriage to Philip, Olympias dreamed that her womb was struck by a thunderbolt that caused a flame to spread "far and wide" before dying away.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Sometime after the wedding, Philip is said to have seen himself, in a dream, securing his wife's womb with a seal engraved with a lion's image.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch offered a variety of interpretations for these dreams: that Olympias was pregnant before her marriage, indicated by the sealing of her womb; or that Alexander's father was Zeus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Ancient commentators were divided about whether the ambitious Olympias promulgated the story of Alexander's divine parentage, variously claiming that she had told Alexander, or that she dismissed the suggestion as impious.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] On the day Alexander was born, Philip was preparing a siege on the city of Potidea on the peninsula of Chalcidice.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] That same day, Philip received news that his general Parmenion had defeated the combined Illyrian and Paeonian armies and that his horses had won at the Olympic Games.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] It was also said that on this day, the Temple of Artemis in Ephesus, one of the Seven Wonders of the World, burnt down.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This led Hegesias of Magnesia to say that it had burnt down because Artemis was away, attending the birth of Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Such legends may have emerged when Alexander was king, and possibly at his instigation, to show that he was superhuman and destined for greatness from conception.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In his early years, Alexander was raised by a nurse, Lanike, sister of Alexander's future general Cleitus the Black.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Later in his childhood, Alexander was tutored by the strict Leonidas, a relative of his mother, and by Lysimachus of Acarnania.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was raised in the manner of noble Macedonian youths, learning to read, play the lyre, ride, fight, and hunt.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was ten years old, a trader from Thessaly brought Philip a horse, which he offered to sell for thirteen talents.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The horse refused to be mounted, and Philip ordered it away.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander, however, detecting the horse's fear of its own shadow, asked to tame the horse, which he eventually managed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch stated that Philip, overjoyed at this display of courage and ambition, kissed his son tearfully, declaring: "My boy, you must find a kingdom big enough for your ambitions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Macedon is too small for you", and bought the horse for him.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander named it Bucephalas, meaning "ox-head".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Bucephalas carried Alexander as far as modern day India.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Bucephalas died (because of old age, according to Plutarch, at age 30), Alexander named a city after him, Bucephala.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was 13, Philip began to search for a tutor, and considered such academics as Isocrates and Speusippus, the latter offering to resign from his stewardship of the Academy to take up the post.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the end, Philip chose Aristotle and provided the Temple of the Nymphs at Mieza as a classroom.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In return for teaching Alexander, Philip agreed to rebuild Aristotle's hometown of Stageira, which Philip had razed, and to repopulate it by buying and freeing the ex-citizens who were slaves, or pardoning those who were in exile.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Mieza was like a boarding school for Alexander and the children of Macedonian nobles, such as Ptolemy, Hephaestion, and Cassander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Many of these students would become his friends and future generals, and are often known as the "Companions".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Aristotle taught Alexander and his companions about medicine, philosophy, morals, religion, logic, and art.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Under Aristotle's tutelage, Alexander developed a passion for the works of Homer, and in particular the *Iliad*; Aristotle gave him an annotated copy, which Alexander later carried on his campaigns.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was able to quote Euripides from memory.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In his youth, Alexander was also acquainted with Persian exiles at the Macedonian court, who received the protection of Philip II for several years as they opposed Artaxerxes III.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Among them were Artabazos II and his daughter Barsine, possible future mistress of Alexander, who resided at the Macedonian court from 352 to 342 BC, as well as Amminapes, future satrap of Alexander, and a Persian nobleman named Sisines.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This gave the Macedonian court a good knowledge of Persian issues, and may even have influenced some of the innovations in the management of the Macedonian state.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Suda writes that Anaximenes of Lampsacus was one of Alexander's teachers, and that Anaximenes also accompanied Alexander on his campaigns.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] At the age of 16, Alexander's education under Aristotle ended.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip II had waged war against the Thracians to the north, which left Alexander in charge as regent and heir apparent.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During Philip's absence, the Thracian tribe of Maedi revolted against Macedonia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander responded quickly and drove them from their territory.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The territory was colonized, and a city, named Alexandropolis, was founded.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Upon Philip's return, Alexander was dispatched with a small force to subdue the revolts in southern Thrace.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Campaigning against the Greek city of Perinthus, Alexander reportedly saved his father's life.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, the city of Amphissa began to work lands that were sacred to Apollo near Delphi, a sacrilege that gave Philip the opportunity to further intervene in Greek affairs.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] While Philip was occupied in Thrace, Alexander was ordered to muster an army for a campaign in southern Greece.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Concerned that other Greek states might intervene, Alexander made it look as though he was preparing to attack Illyria instead.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During this turmoil, the Illyrians invaded Macedonia, only to be repelled by Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip and his army joined his son in 338 BC, and they marched south through Thermopylae, taking it after stubborn resistance from its Theban garrison.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] They went on to occupy the city of Elatea, only a few days' march from both Athens and Thebes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Athenians, led by Demosthenes, voted to seek alliance with Thebes against Macedonia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Both Athens and Philip sent embassies to win Thebes's favour, but Athens won the contest.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip marched on Amphissa (ostensibly acting on the request of the Amphictyonic League), capturing the mercenaries sent there by Demosthenes and accepting the city's surrender.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip then returned to Elatea, sending a final offer of peace to Athens and Thebes, who both rejected it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] As Philip marched south, his opponents blocked him near Chaeronea, Boeotia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During the ensuing Battle of Chaeronea, Philip commanded the right wing and Alexander the left, accompanied by a group of Philip's trusted generals.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient sources, the two sides fought bitterly for some time.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip deliberately commanded his troops to retreat, counting on the untested Athenian hoplites to follow, thus breaking their line.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was the first to break the Theban lines, followed by Philip's generals.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Having damaged the enemy's cohesion, Philip ordered his troops to press forward and quickly routed them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] With the Athenians lost, the Thebans were surrounded.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Left to fight alone, they were defeated.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Following their victory at Chaeronea, Philip and Alexander marched unopposed into the Peloponnese, devastating much of Laconia and ejecting the Spartans from various parts of it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] At Corinth, Philip established a "Hellenic Alliance" (modelled on the old anti-Persian alliance of the Greco-Persian Wars), which included most Greek city-states except Sparta.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip was then named *Hegemon* (often translated as "Supreme Commander") of this league (known by modern scholars as the League of Corinth), and announced his plans to attack the Persian Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip returned to Pella, he fell in love with and married Cleopatra Eurydice in 338 BC, the niece of his general Attalus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The marriage made Alexander's position as heir less secure, since any son of Cleopatra Eurydice would be a fully Macedonian heir, while Alexander was only half-Macedonian.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During the wedding banquet, a drunken Attalus publicly prayed to the gods that the union would produce a legitimate heir.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] — Plutarch, describing the feud at Philip's wedding.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In 337 BC, Alexander fled Macedon with his mother, dropping her off with her brother, King Alexander I of Epirus in Dodona, capital of the Molossians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He continued to Illyria where he sought refuge with one or more Illyrian kings, perhaps with Glaucias, and was treated as a guest, despite having defeated them in battle a few years before.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] However, it appears Philip never intended to disown his politically and militarily trained son.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Accordingly, Alexander returned to Macedon after six months due to the efforts of a family friend, Demaratus, who mediated between the two parties.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, the Persian satrap (governor) of Caria, Pixodarus, offered his eldest daughter to Alexander's half-brother, Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias and several of Alexander's friends suggested this showed Philip intended to make Arrhidaeus his heir.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reacted by sending an actor, Thessalus of Corinth, to tell Pixodarus that he should not offer his daughter's hand to an illegitimate son, but instead to Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip heard of this, he stopped the negotiations and scolded Alexander for wishing to marry the daughter of a Carian, explaining that he wanted a better bride for him.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip exiled four of Alexander's friends, Harpalus, Nearchus, Ptolemy and Erigyius, and had the Corinthians bring Thessalus to him in chains.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] As Pausanias tried to escape, he tripped over a vine and was killed by his pursuers, including two of Alexander's companions, Perdiccas and Leonnatus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was proclaimed king on the spot by the nobles and army at the age of 20.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander began his reign by eliminating potential rivals to the throne.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He had his cousin, the former Amyntas IV, executed and two Macedonian princes from the region of Lyncestis killed for having been involved in his father's assassination, but spared a third, Alexander Lyncestes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias had Cleopatra Eurydice, and Europa, her daughter by Philip, burned alive, though this infuriated Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander also ordered the murder of Cleopatra's uncle Attalus, who was in command of the advance guard of the army in Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Attalus was at that time corresponding with Demosthenes regarding the possibility of defecting to Athens, and had severely insulted Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After his niece's murder, Alexander may have considered him too dangerous to be left alive.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander spared Arrhidaeus, who was by all accounts mentally disabled, possibly as a result of poisoning by Olympias.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] News of Philip's death roused many states into revolt, including Thebes, Athens, Thessaly, and the Thracian tribes north of Macedon.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When news of the revolts reached Alexander, he responded quickly.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Though advised to use diplomacy, Alexander mustered 3,000 Macedonian cavalry and rode south towards Thessaly.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He found the Thessalian army occupying the pass between Mount Olympus and Mount Ossa, and ordered his men to ride over Mount Ossa.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When the Thessalians awoke the next day, they found Alexander in their rear and promptly surrendered, adding their cavalry to Alexander's force.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He then continued south towards the Peloponnese.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stopped at Thermopylae where he was recognized as the leader of the Amphictyonic League before heading south to Corinth.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Athens sued for peace and Alexander pardoned the rebels.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The famous encounter between Alexander and Diogenes the Cynic occurred during Alexander's stay in Corinth.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander asked Diogenes what he could do for him, the philosopher disdainfully asked Alexander to stand a little to the side, as he was blocking the sunlight.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This reply apparently delighted Alexander who is reported to have said, "But verily, if I were not Alexander, I would like to be Diogenes." At Corinth, Alexander took the title of *Hegemon* ("leader") and, like Philip, was appointed commander for the coming war against Persia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He also received news of a Thracian uprising.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Before crossing to Asia, Alexander wanted to safeguard his northern borders.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the spring of 335 BC, he advanced to suppress several revolts.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Starting from Amphipolis, he travelled east into the country of the "Independent Thracians", and at Mount Haemus, the Macedonian army attacked and defeated the Thracian forces manning the heights.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians marched into the country of the Triballi and defeated their army near the Lyginus river (a tributary of the Danube).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then marched for three days to the Danube, encountering the Getae tribe on the opposite shore.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Crossing the river at night, he surprised them and forced their army to retreat after the first cavalry skirmish.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] News then reached Alexander that the Illyrian chieftain Cleitus and King Glaukias of the Taulantii were in open revolt against his authority.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Marching west into Illyria, Alexander defeated each in turn, forcing the two rulers to flee with their troops.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] With these victories, he secured his northern frontier.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] While Alexander campaigned north, the Thebans and Athenians rebelled once again.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] While the other cities again hesitated, Thebes decided to fight.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Theban resistance was ineffective and Alexander razed the city and divided its territory between the other Boeotian cities.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The end of Thebes cowed Athens, leaving all of Greece temporarily at peace.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then set out on his Asian campaign, leaving Antipater as regent.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After securing his Greek base and the Balkans by subjugating his political opponents, and securing his army's rear through the conquest of all the Afro-Asian coastline, where the Persian fleet was based and from which it was supplied, Alexander moved to confront directly the Persians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In 336 he sent Parmenion, Amyntas, Andromenes, Attalus, and an army of 10,000 men into Anatolia to make preparations for an invasion.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greek cities on the western coast of Anatolia revolted until the news arrived that Philip had been murdered and had been succeeded by his young son Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians were demoralized by Philip's death and were subsequently defeated near Magnesia by the Achaemenids under the command of the mercenary Memnon of Rhodes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He showed his intent to conquer the entirety of the Persian Empire by throwing a spear into Asian soil and saying he accepted Asia as a gift from the gods.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This also showed Alexander's eagerness to fight, in contrast to his father's preference for diplomacy.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After an initial victory against Persian forces at the Battle of the Granicus, Alexander accepted the surrender of the Persian provincial capital and treasury of Sardis; he then proceeded along the Ionian coast, granting autonomy and democracy to the cities.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Miletus, held by Achaemenid forces, required a delicate siege operation, with Persian naval forces nearby.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Further south, at Halicarnassus, in Caria, Alexander successfully waged his first large-scale siege, eventually forcing his opponents, the mercenary captain Memnon of Rhodes and the Persian satrap of Caria, Orontobates, to withdraw by sea.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander left the government of Caria to a member of the Hecatomnid dynasty, Ada, who adopted Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] From Halicarnassus, Alexander proceeded into mountainous Lycia and the Pamphylian plain, asserting control over all coastal cities to deny the Persians naval bases.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] From Pamphylia onwards, the coast held no major ports and Alexander moved inland.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] At Termessos, Alexander humbled and did not storm the Pisidian city.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] At the ancient Phrygian capital of Gordium, Alexander "undid" the hitherto unsolvable Gordian Knot, a feat said to await the future "king of Asia".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the story, Alexander proclaimed that it did not matter how the knot was undone, and hacked it apart with his sword.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In spring 333 BC, Alexander crossed the Taurus into Cilicia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After a long pause due to an illness, he marched on towards Syria.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Though outmanoeuvered by Darius's significantly larger army, he marched back to Cilicia, where he defeated Darius at Issus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled the battle, causing his army to collapse, and left behind his wife, his two daughters, his mother Sisygambis, and a fabulous treasure.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He offered a peace treaty that included the lands he had lost, and a ransom of 10,000 talents for his family.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander replied that since he was now king of Asia, it was he alone who decided territorial divisions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander proceeded to take possession of Syria, and most of the coast of the Levant.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, 332 BC, he was forced to attack Tyre, which he captured after a long and difficult siege.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The men of military age were massacred and the women and children sold into slavery.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander destroyed Tyre, most of the towns on the route to Egypt quickly capitulated.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander was met with resistance at Gaza.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The stronghold was heavily fortified and built on a hill, requiring a siege.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When "his engineers pointed out to him that because of the height of the mound it would be impossible... this encouraged Alexander all the more to make the attempt".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After three unsuccessful assaults, the stronghold fell, but not before Alexander had received a serious shoulder wound.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] As in Tyre, men of military age were put to the sword, and the women and children were sold into slavery.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander advanced on Egypt in later 332 BC where he was regarded as a liberator.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] To legitimize taking power and be recognized as the descendant of the long line of pharaohs, Alexander made sacrifices to the gods at Memphis and went to consult the famous oracle of Amun-Ra at the Siwa Oasis in the Libyan desert, at which he was pronounced the son of the deity Amun.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Henceforth, Alexander often referred to Zeus-Ammon as his true father, and after his death, currency depicted him adorned with horns, using the Horns of Ammon as a symbol of his divinity.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks interpreted this message – one that the gods addressed to all pharaohs – as a prophecy.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Egypt was only one of a large number of territories taken by Alexander from the Persians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After his trip to Siwa, Alexander was crowned in the temple of Ptah at Memphis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] It appears that the Egyptian people did not find it disturbing that he was a foreigner – nor that he was absent for virtually his entire reign.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander restored the temples neglected by the Persians and dedicated new monuments to the Egyptian gods.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the temple of Luxor, near Karnak, he built a chapel for the sacred barge.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During his brief months in Egypt, he reformed the taxation system on the Greek models and organized the military occupation of the country, but in early 331 BC he left for Asia in pursuit of the Persians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay in Egypt, he founded Alexandria, which would become the prosperous capital of the Ptolemaic Kingdom after his death.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Control of Egypt passed to Ptolemy I (son of Lagos), the founder of the Ptolemaic Dynasty (305–30 BC) after the death of Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Leaving Egypt in 331 BC, Alexander marched eastward into Achaemenid Assyria in Upper Mesopotamia (now northern Iraq) and defeated Darius again at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius once more fled the field, and Alexander chased him as far as Arbela.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Gaugamela would be the final and decisive encounter between the two.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled over the mountains to Ecbatana (modern Hamadan) while Alexander captured Babylon.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Babylonian astronomical diaries say that "the king of the world, Alexander" sent his scouts with a message to the people of Babylon before entering the city: "I shall not enter your houses".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] From Babylon, Alexander went to Susa, one of the Achaemenid capitals, and captured its treasury.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He sent the bulk of his army to the Persian ceremonial capital of Persepolis via the Persian Royal Road.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander himself took selected troops on the direct route to the city.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He then stormed the pass of the Persian Gates (in the modern Zagros Mountains) which had been blocked by a Persian army under Ariobarzanes and then hurried to Persepolis before its garrison could loot the treasury.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] On entering Persepolis, Alexander allowed his troops to loot the city for several days.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stayed in Persepolis for five months.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay, a fire broke out in the eastern palace of Xerxes I and spread to the rest of the city.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Possible causes include a drunken accident or deliberate revenge for the burning of the Acropolis of Athens during the Second Persian War by Xerxes; Plutarch and Diodorus allege that Alexander's companion, the hetaera Thaïs, instigated and started the fire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Even as he watched the city burn, Alexander immediately began to regret his decision.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch claims that he ordered his men to put out the fires but the flames had already spread to most of the city.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Curtius claims that Alexander did not regret his decision until the next morning.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then chased Darius, first into Media, and then Parthia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Persian king no longer controlled his own destiny, and was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men fatally stab the Great King and then declared himself Darius's successor as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia to launch a guerrilla campaign against Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander buried Darius's remains next to his Achaemenid predecessors in a regal funeral.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He claimed that, while dying, Darius had named him as his successor to the Achaemenid throne.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is normally considered to have fallen with Darius.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander viewed Bessus as an usurper and set out to defeat him.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This campaign, initially against Bessus, turned into a grand tour of central Asia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded a series of new cities, all called Alexandria, including modern Kandahar in Afghanistan, and Alexandria Eschate ("The Furthest") in modern Tajikistan.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The campaign took Alexander through a number of satrapies in present-day Afghanistan and Central Asia, including Media, Parthia, Aria, Drangiana, Arachosia, Bactria, and Scythia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In 329 BC, Spitamenes, who held an undefined position in the satrapy of Sogdiana, betrayed Bessus to Ptolemy, one of Alexander's trusted companions, and Bessus was executed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] However, at some point later when Alexander was on the Jaxartes dealing with an incursion by a horse nomad army, Spitamenes raised Sogdiana in revolt.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander personally defeated the Scythians at the Battle of Jaxartes and immediately launched a campaign against Spitamenes, defeating him in the Battle of Gabai.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After the defeat, Spitamenes was killed by his own men, who then sued for peace.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During this time, Alexander adopted some elements of Persian dress and customs at his court, notably the custom of *proskynesis*, either a symbolic kissing of the hand, or prostration on the ground, that Persians showed to their social superiors.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This was one aspect of Alexander's broad strategy aimed at securing the aid and support of the Iranian upper classes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks however regarded the gesture of *proskynesis* as the province of deities and believed that Alexander meant to deify himself by requiring it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen, and he eventually abandoned it.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During the long rule of the Achaemenids, the elite positions in many segments of the empire including the central government, the army, and the many satrapies were specifically reserved for Iranians and to a major degree, Persian noblemen.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The latter were in many cases additionally connected through marriage alliances with the royal Achaemenid family.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This created a problem for Alexander as to whether he had to make use of the various segments and people that had given the empire its solidity and unity for a lengthy period of time.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Pierre Briant explains that Alexander realized that it was insufficient to merely exploit the internal contradictions within the imperial system as in Asia Minor, Babylonia or Egypt; he also had to (re)create a central government with or without the support of the Iranians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] As early as 334 BC he demonstrated awareness of this, when he challenged incumbent King Darius III "by appropriating the main elements of the Achaemenid monarchy's ideology, particularly the theme of the king who protects the lands and the peasants".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander wrote a letter in 332 BC to Darius III, wherein he argued that he was worthier than Darius "to succeed to the Achaemenid throne".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's eventual decision to burn the Achaemenid palace at Persepolis in conjunction with the major rejection and opposition of the "entire Persian people" made it impracticable for him to pose himself as Darius' legitimate successor.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Against Bessus (Artaxerxes V) however, Briant adds, Alexander reasserted "his claim to legitimacy as the avenger of Darius III".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] A plot against his life was revealed, and one of his officers, Philotas, was executed for failing to alert Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The death of the son necessitated the death of the father, and thus Parmenion, who had been charged with guarding the treasury at Ecbatana, was assassinated at Alexander's command, to prevent attempts at vengeance.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Later, in the Central Asian campaign, a second plot against his life was revealed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This one was instigated by his own royal pages.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] His official historian, Callisthenes of Olynthus, was implicated in the plot, and in the *Anabasis of Alexander*, Arrian states that Callisthenes and the pages were then tortured on the rack as punishment, and likely died soon after.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] It remains unclear if Callisthenes was actually involved in the plot, for prior to his accusation he had fallen out of favour by leading the opposition to the attempt to introduce proskynesis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander set out for Asia, he left his general Antipater, an experienced military and political leader, and part of Philip II's "Old Guard", in charge of Macedon.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's sacking of Thebes ensured that Greece remained quiet during his absence.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The one exception was a call to arms by Spartan king Agis III in 331 BC, whom Antipater defeated and killed in the battle of Megalopolis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Antipater referred the Spartans' punishment to the League of Corinth, which then deferred to Alexander, who chose to pardon them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] There was also considerable friction between Antipater and Olympias, and each complained to Alexander about the other.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In general, Greece enjoyed a period of peace and prosperity during Alexander's campaign in Asia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent back vast sums from his conquest, which stimulated the economy and increased trade across his empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's constant demands for troops and the migration of Macedonians throughout his empire depleted Macedon's strength, greatly weakening it in the years after Alexander, and ultimately led to its subjugation by Rome after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BC).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The conquest by Philip II of Pangaeum, and then of the island of Thasos between 356 and 342 BC brought rich gold and silver mines under Macedonian control.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander appears to have introduced a new coinage in Cilicia in Tarsus, after the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, which went on to become the main coinage of the empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander minted gold staters, silver tetradrachms and drachims, and various fractional bronze coins.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The types of these coins remained constant in his empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The gold series had the head of Athena on the obverse and a winged Nike (Victory) on the reverse.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The silver coinage had a beardless head of Heracles wearing a lionskin headdress on the obverse and Zeus aetophoros ('eagle bearer') enthroned with a scepter in his left hand, on the reverse.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] There are both Greek and non-Greek aspects to this design.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Heracles and Zeus were important deities for the Macedonians, with Heracles considered to be the ancestor of the Temenid dynasty and Zeus the patron of the main Macedonian sanctuary, Dium.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The lion was also the symbolic animal of the Anatolian god Sandas, worshipped at Tarsus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The reverse design of Alexander's tetradrachms is closely modelled on the depiction of the god Baaltars (Baal of Tarsus), on the silver staters minted at Tarsus by the Persian satrap Mazaeus before Alexander's conquest.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander did not attempt to impose uniform imperial coinage throughout his new conquests.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Persian coins continued to circulate in all the satrapies of the empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Spitamenes and his marriage to Roxana (Raoxshna in Old Iranian) to cement relations with his new satrapies, Alexander turned to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He invited the chieftains of the former satrapy of Gandhara (in the present-day Peshawar Valley), to come to him and submit to his authority.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the winter of 327/326 BC, Alexander personally led Cophen campaign against the Aspasioi of the Kunar Valley, the Guraeans of the Panjkora Valley, and the Assakenoi of the Swat Valley.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] A fierce contest ensued with the Aspasioi in which Alexander was wounded in the shoulder by a dart, but eventually the Aspasioi lost.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then faced the Assakenoi who fought against him from the strongholds of Massaga, Ora, and Aornos.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The fort of Massaga was reduced after days of bloody fighting in which Alexander was seriously wounded in the ankle.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] According to Curtius, "Not only did Alexander slaughter the entire population of Massaga, but also did he reduce its buildings to rubble." A similar massacre followed at Ora.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In the aftermath of Massaga and Ora, numerous Assakenians fled to the fortress of Aornos.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander followed close behind and captured the strategic hill-fort after four bloody days.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Assakenoi leader, his mother queen Cleophis submitted to Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After Aornos, Alexander crossed the Indus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis hastened to relieve Alexander of his apprehension and met him with valuable presents, placing himself and all his forces at his disposal.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander not only returned Omphis his title and the gifts but he also presented him with a wardrobe of "Persian robes, gold and silver ornaments, 30 horses and 1,000 talents in gold".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] On the subsequent advance of the Macedonian king, Omphis accompanied him with a force of 5,000 men and took part in the Battle of the Hydaspes against the King Porus, who ruled territory lying between the Hydaspes and the Acesines (Chenab) in the Punjab, in 326 BC.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander won an epic battle against Porus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis was sent by Alexander in pursuit of Porus, to whom he was charged to offer favourable terms, but narrowly escaped losing his life at the hands of his old enemy.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Subsequently, the two rivals were reconciled by the personal mediation of Alexander; Omphis contributed zealously to the equipment of the fleet on the Hydaspes and was entrusted by Alexander with the government of the whole territory between that river and the Indus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was also impressed by Porus's bravery and made him an ally.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] He appointed Porus as satrap, and added to Porus's territory land that he did not previously own, towards the south-east, up to the Hyphasis (Beas).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Choosing local rulers helped him control these lands that were distant from Greece.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] A considerable accession of power was granted him after the death of Philip, son of Machatas, and he was allowed to retain his authority at the death of Alexander himself (323 BC), as well as in the subsequent partition of the provinces at Triparadisus, 321 BC.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded two cities on opposite sides of the Hydaspes river, naming one Bucephala, in honour of his horse, who died around this time.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The other was Nicaea (Victory), believed to be located at the site of modern-day Mong.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Philostratus the Elder in the *Life of Apollonius of Tyana* writes that in the army of Porus, there was an elephant who fought bravely against Alexander's army, and Alexander dedicated it to the Helios (Sun) and named it Ajax because he thought that such a great animal deserved a great name.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The elephant had gold rings around its tusks and an inscription was on them written in Greek: "Alexander the son of Zeus dedicates Ajax to the Helios" (ΑΛΕΞΑΝΔΡΟΣ Ο ΔΙΟΣ ΤΟΝ ΑΙΑΝΤΑ ΤΩΙ ΗΛΙΩΙ).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] East of Porus's kingdom, near the Ganges River, was the Nanda Empire of Magadha, and further east, the Gangaridai Empire of Bengal region.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Fearing the prospect of facing other large armies and exhausted by years of campaigning, Alexander's army mutinied at the Hyphasis River (Beas), refusing to march farther east.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] This river thus marks the easternmost extent of Alexander's conquests.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander tried to persuade his soldiers to march farther, but his general Coenus pleaded with him to change his opinion and return; the men, he said, "longed to again see their parents, their wives and children, their homeland".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander eventually agreed and turned south, marching along the Indus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Along the way his army conquered the territory inhabited by the Mallians in the Mallian campaign; while besieging the Mallian citadel, Alexander suffered a near-fatal injury when an arrow penetrated his armor and entered his lung.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent much of his army to Carmania (modern southern Iran) with general Craterus, and commissioned a fleet to explore the Persian Gulf shore under his admiral Nearchus, while he led the rest back to Persia through the more difficult southern route along the Gedrosian Desert and Makran.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reached Susa in 324 BC, but not before losing many men to the harsh desert.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Discovering that many of his satraps and military governors had misbehaved in his absence, Alexander executed several of them as examples on his way to Susa.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] As a gesture of thanks, he paid off the debts of his soldiers, and announced he would send over-aged and disabled veterans back to Macedon, led by Craterus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] His troops misunderstood his intention and mutinied at the town of Opis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] They refused to be sent away and criticized his adoption of Persian customs and dress and the introduction of Persian officers and soldiers into Macedonian units.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] After three days, unable to persuade his men to back down, Alexander gave Persians command posts in the army and conferred Macedonian military titles upon Persian units.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians quickly begged forgiveness, which Alexander accepted, and held a great banquet with several thousand of his men.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] In an attempt to craft a lasting harmony between his Macedonian and Persian subjects, Alexander held a mass marriage of his senior officers to Persian and other noblewomen at Susa, but few of those marriages seem to have lasted much beyond a year.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, upon his return to Persia, Alexander learned that guards of the tomb of Cyrus the Great in Pasargadae had desecrated it, and swiftly executed them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander admired Cyrus the Great, from an early age reading Xenophon's *Cyropaedia*, which described Cyrus's heroism in battle and governance as a king and legislator.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] During his visit to Pasargadae, Alexander ordered his architect Aristobulus to decorate the interior of the sepulchral chamber of Cyrus's tomb.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Afterwards, Alexander travelled to Ecbatana to retrieve the bulk of the Persian treasure.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] There, his closest friend, Hephaestion, died of illness or poisoning.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander and he ordered the preparation of an expensive funeral pyre in Babylon along with a decree for public mourning.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p01] Back in Babylon, Alexander planned a series of new campaigns, beginning with an invasion of Arabia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] On either 10 or 11 June 323 BC, Alexander died in the palace of Nebuchadnezzar II, in Babylon, at age 32.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] There are two different versions of Alexander's death, differing slightly in details.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Plutarch's account is that roughly 14 days before his death, Alexander entertained admiral Nearchus and spent the night and next day drinking with Medius of Larissa.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander developed a fever, which worsened until he was unable to speak.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The common soldiers, anxious about his health, were granted the right to file past him as he silently waved at them.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] In the second account, Diodorus recounts that Alexander was struck with pain after downing a large bowl of unmixed wine in honour of Heracles followed by 11 days of weakness; he did not develop a fever, instead dying after some agony.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian also mentioned this as an alternative, but Plutarch specifically denied this claim.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Given the propensity of the Macedonian aristocracy to assassination and Alexander's relatively young age, foul play featured in multiple accounts of his death.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Plutarch, Arrian and Justin all mentioned the theory that Alexander was poisoned.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Justin stated that Alexander was the victim of a poisoning conspiracy, Plutarch dismissed it as a fabrication, while both Diodorus and Arrian noted that they mentioned it only for the sake of completeness.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The accounts were nevertheless fairly consistent in designating Antipater, recently removed as Macedonian viceroy, replaced by Craterus, as the head of the alleged plot.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps taking his summons to Babylon as a death sentence and having seen the fate of Parmenion and Philotas, Antipater purportedly arranged for Alexander to be poisoned by his son Iollas, who was Alexander's wine-pourer.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] There was even a suggestion that Aristotle may have participated.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The strongest argument against the poison theory is the fact that twelve days passed between the start of his illness and his death; such long-acting poisons were probably not available.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in a 2003 BBC documentary investigating the death of Alexander, Leo Schep from the New Zealand National Poisons Centre proposed that the plant white hellebore (*Veratrum album*), which was known in antiquity, may have been used to poison Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] In a 2014 manuscript in the journal *Clinical Toxicology*, Schep suggested Alexander's wine was spiked with *Veratrum album*, and that this would produce poisoning symptoms that match the course of events described in the *Alexander Romance*.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] *Veratrum album* poisoning can have a prolonged course and it was suggested that if Alexander was poisoned, *Veratrum album* offers the most plausible cause.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Another poisoning explanation put forward in 2010 proposed that the circumstances of his death were compatible with poisoning by water of the river Styx (modern-day Mavroneri in Arcadia, Greece) that contained calicheamicin, a dangerous compound produced by bacteria.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Several natural causes (diseases) have been suggested, including malaria and typhoid fever.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] A 1998 article in the *New England Journal of Medicine* attributed his death to typhoid fever complicated by bowel perforation and ascending paralysis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] A 2004 analysis suggested pyogenic (infectious) spondylitis or meningitis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Other illnesses fit the symptoms, including acute pancreatitis, West Nile virus, and Guillain-Barré syndrome.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Natural-cause theories also tend to emphasize that Alexander's health may have been in general decline after years of heavy drinking and severe wounds.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The anguish that Alexander felt after Hephaestion's death may also have contributed to his declining health.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's body was laid in a gold anthropoid sarcophagus that was filled with honey, which was in turn placed in a gold casket.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Aelian, a seer called Aristander foretold that the land where Alexander was laid to rest "would be happy and unvanquishable forever".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps more likely, the successors may have seen possession of the body as a symbol of legitimacy, since burying the prior king was a royal prerogative.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander's funeral cortege was on its way to Macedon, Ptolemy seized it and took it temporarily to Memphis.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] His successor, Ptolemy II Philadelphus, transferred the sarcophagus to Alexandria, where it remained until at least late antiquity.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Ptolemy IX Lathyros, one of Ptolemy's final successors, replaced Alexander's sarcophagus with a glass one so he could convert the original to coinage.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The 2014 discovery of an enormous tomb in northern Greece, at Amphipolis, dating from the time of Alexander the Great has given rise to speculation that its original intent was to be the burial place of Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This would fit with the intended destination of Alexander's funeral cortege.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the memorial was found to be dedicated to the dearest friend of Alexander the Great, Hephaestion.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey, Julius Caesar and Augustus all visited the tomb in Alexandria where Augustus, allegedly, accidentally knocked the nose of Alexander's mummified body off.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula was said to have taken Alexander's breastplate from the tomb for his own use.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Around AD 200, Emperor Septimius Severus closed Alexander's tomb to the public.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] His son and successor, Caracalla, a great admirer, visited the tomb during his own reign.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] After this, details on the fate of the tomb are hazy.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The so-called "Alexander Sarcophagus", discovered near Sidon and now in the Istanbul Archaeology Museum, is so named not because it was thought to have contained Alexander's remains, but because its bas-reliefs depict Alexander and his companions fighting the Persians and hunting.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] It was originally thought to have been the sarcophagus of Abdalonymus (died 311 BC), the king of Sidon appointed by Alexander immediately following the Battle of Issus in 332.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1969, it was suggested by Karl Schefold that it may date from earlier than Abdalonymus's death.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Demades likened the Macedonian army, after the death of Alexander, to the blinded Cyclops due to the many random and disorderly movements that it made.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] In addition, Leosthenes also likened the anarchy between the generals, after Alexander's death, to the blinded Cyclops "who after he had lost his eye went feeling and groping about with his hands before him, not knowing where to lay them".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's death was so sudden that when reports of his death reached Greece, they were not immediately believed.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander had no obvious or legitimate heir, his son Alexander IV by Roxane being born after Alexander's death.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's companions asked him on his deathbed to whom he bequeathed his kingdom; his laconic reply was "tôi kratistôi"—"to the strongest".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Another theory is that his successors wilfully or erroneously misheard "tôi Kraterôi"—"to Craterus", the general leading his Macedonian troops home and newly entrusted with the regency of Macedonia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian and Plutarch claimed that Alexander was speechless by this time, implying that this was an apocryphal story.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Curtius and Justin offered the more plausible story that Alexander passed his signet ring to Perdiccas, a bodyguard and leader of the companion cavalry, in front of witnesses, thereby nominating him.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Perdiccas initially did not claim power, instead suggesting that Roxane's baby would be king, if male, with himself, Craterus, Leonnatus, and Antipater as guardians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the infantry, under the command of Meleager, rejected this arrangement since they had been excluded from the discussion.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Instead, they supported Alexander's half-brother Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Eventually, the two sides reconciled, and after the birth of Alexander IV, he and Philip III were appointed joint kings, albeit in name only.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Dissension and rivalry soon affected the Macedonians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The satrapies handed out by Perdiccas at the Partition of Babylon became power bases each general used to bid for power.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] After the assassination of Perdiccas in 321 BC, Macedonian unity collapsed, and 40 years of war between "The Successors" (*Diadochi*) ensued before the Hellenistic world settled into three stable power blocs: Ptolemaic Egypt, Seleucid Syria and Persia, and Antigonid Macedonia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] In the process, both Alexander IV and Philip III were murdered.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus stated that Alexander had given detailed written instructions to Craterus some time before his death, which are known as Alexander's "last plans".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Craterus started to carry out Alexander's commands, but the successors chose not to further implement them, on the grounds they were impractical and extravagant.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, Perdiccas had read the notebooks containing Alexander's last plans to the Macedonian troops in Babylon, who voted not to carry them out.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's last plans called for military expansion into the southern and western Mediterranean, monumental constructions, and the intermixing of Eastern and Western populations.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The enormous scale of these plans has led many scholars to doubt their historicity.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Ernst Badian argued that they were exaggerated by Perdiccas in order to ensure that the Macedonian troops voted not to carry them out.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Other scholars have proposed that they were invented by later authors within the tradition of the Alexander Romance.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander perhaps earned the epithet "the Great" due to his unparalleled success as a military commander; he never lost a battle, despite typically being outnumbered.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This was due to use of terrain, phalanx and cavalry tactics, bold strategy, and the fierce loyalty of his troops.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macedonian phalanx, armed with the sarissa, a spear 6 metres (20 ft) long, had been developed and perfected by Philip II through rigorous training, and Alexander used its speed and manoeuvrability to great effect against larger but more disparate Persian forces.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also recognized the potential for disunity among his diverse army, which employed various languages and weapons.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He overcame this by being personally involved in battle, in the manner of a Macedonian king.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] In his first battle in Asia, at Granicus, Alexander used only a small part of his forces, perhaps 13,000 infantry with 5,000 cavalry, against a much larger Persian force of 40,000.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander placed the phalanx at the center and cavalry and archers on the wings, so that his line matched the length of the Persian cavalry line, about 3 km (1.86 mi).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] By contrast, the Persian infantry was stationed behind its cavalry.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This ensured that Alexander would not be outflanked, while his phalanx, armed with long pikes, had a considerable advantage over the Persians' scimitars and javelins.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Macedonian losses were negligible compared to those of the Persians.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] At Issus in 333 BC, his first confrontation with Darius, he used the same deployment, and again the central phalanx pushed through.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander personally led the charge in the center, routing the opposing army.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] At the decisive encounter with Darius at Gaugamela, Darius equipped his chariots with scythes on the wheels to break up the phalanx and equipped his cavalry with pikes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander arranged a double phalanx, with the center advancing at an angle, parting when the chariots bore down and then reforming.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The advance was successful and broke Darius's center, causing the latter to flee once again.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] When faced with opponents who used unfamiliar fighting techniques, such as in Central Asia and India, Alexander adapted his forces to his opponents' style.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, in Bactria and Sogdiana, Alexander successfully used his javelin throwers and archers to prevent outflanking movements, while massing his cavalry at the center.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] In India, confronted by Porus's elephant corps, the Macedonians opened their ranks to envelop the elephants and used their sarissas to strike upwards and dislodge the elephants' handlers.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Historical sources frequently give conflicting accounts of Alexander's appearance, and the earliest sources are the most scant in their detail; for example, Arrian describes him simply as "very handsome".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] During his lifetime, Alexander carefully curated his image by commissioning works from famous and great artists of the time.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This included commissioning sculptures by Lysippos, paintings by Apelles and gem engravings by Pyrgoteles.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Ancient authors recorded that Alexander was so pleased with portraits of himself created by Lysippos that he forbade other sculptors from crafting his image; scholars today, however, find the claim dubious.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, though idealised, Lysippos's sculpture was thought to be the most faithful plastic representation.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] 3rd century BC bust of Alexander from Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Both Curtius and Diodorus report a story that when Darius III's mother, Sisygambis, first met Alexander and Hephaestion, she assumed that the latter was Alexander because he was the taller and more physically impressive of the two.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Historians have understood the detail of the pleasant fragrance attributed to Alexander as stemming from a belief in ancient Greece that pleasant scents are characteristic of gods and heroes.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The Alexander Mosaic and contemporary coins portray Alexander with "a straight nose, a slightly protruding jaw, full lips and eyes deep set beneath a strongly pronounced forehead".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He is also described as having a slight upward tilt of his head to the left.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] 235 AD), in his *Varia Historia* (12.14), describes Alexander's hair color as "ξανθὴν" (*xanthen*), which at the time, could mean blond, brown, tawny (light brown) or auburn.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] It is sometimes claimed that Alexander had one blue and one brown eye, referring to the *Alexander Romance*, which is however a fictional account that also claims Alexander "had sharp teeth like fangs" and "did not look like Philip or Olympias".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Reconstruction, based on remaining traces of paint of the original polychromy on the Alexander Sarcophagus from Sidon, indicates that he was depicted with brown eyes and chestnut brown hair.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The Acropolis Museum suggests that trace amounts of red paint on a head statue of Alexander found in 1886 were most likely a base coat for golden hues to be painted over for his hair.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The Pella mosaic of a lion hunt (late 4th century BC) depicts him as having blond hair, with empty spots where their eye stones (which would've been used with semi-precious gems) having been plucked out.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Both of Alexander's parents encouraged his ambitions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] His father Philip was probably Alexander's most immediate and influential role model, as the young Alexander watched him campaign practically every year, winning victory after victory while ignoring severe wounds.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's relationship with his father "forged" the competitive side of his personality; he had a need to outdo his father, illustrated by his reckless behavior in battle.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander worried that his father would leave him "no great or brilliant achievement to be displayed to the world", he also downplayed his father's achievements to his companions.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's mother Olympias similarly had huge ambitions, and encouraged her son to believe it was his destiny to conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] She instilled a sense of destiny in him, and Plutarch tells how his ambition "kept his spirit serious and lofty in advance of his years".
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Plutarch, Alexander also had a violent temper and rash, impulsive nature, which could influence his decision making.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Although Alexander was stubborn and did not respond well to orders from his father, he was open to reasoned debate.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a calmer side—perceptive, logical, and calculating.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a great desire for knowledge, a love for philosophy, and was an avid reader.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This was no doubt in part due to Aristotle's tutelage; Alexander was intelligent and quick to learn.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] His intelligent and rational side was amply demonstrated by his ability and success as a general.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great self-restraint in "pleasures of the body", in contrast with his lack of self-control with alcohol.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was erudite and patronized both arts and sciences.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] However, he had little interest in sports or the Olympic Games (unlike his father), seeking only the Homeric ideals of honour (*timê*) and glory (*kudos*).
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great charisma and force of personality, characteristics which made him a great leader.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] His unique abilities were further demonstrated by the inability of any of his generals to unite Macedonia and retain the Empire after his death—only Alexander had the ability to do so.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] During his final years, and especially after the death of Hephaestion, Alexander began to exhibit signs of megalomania and paranoia.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] His extraordinary achievements, coupled with his own ineffable sense of destiny and the flattery of his companions, may have combined to produce this effect.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] His delusions of grandeur are readily visible in his will and in his desire to conquer the world, in as much as he is by various sources described as having *boundless ambition*, an epithet, the meaning of which has descended into a historical cliché.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He appears to have believed himself a deity, or at least sought to deify himself.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Olympias always insisted to him that he was the son of Zeus, an idea apparently confirmed to him by the oracle of Amun at Siwa.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] He began to identify himself as the son of Zeus-Ammon.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This behaviour cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also was a pragmatic ruler who understood the difficulties of ruling culturally disparate peoples, many of whom lived in societies where the king was treated as divine.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, rather than megalomania, his behaviour may have been a practical attempt at strengthening his rule and keeping his empire together.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander married three times: Roxana, daughter of the Sogdian nobleman Oxyartes of Bactria, out of love; the Persian princesses Stateira and Parysatis, the former a daughter of Darius III and the latter a daughter of Artaxerxes III, for political reasons.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander apparently had two children by Roxana: a son, who was born in India and died in infancy in November 326 BC, and Alexander IV of Macedon, born after his father's death.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Additionally Heracles of Macedon was claimed to be his illegitimate son born of mistress, Barsine.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also had a close relationship with his friend, general, and bodyguard Hephaestion, the son of a Macedonian noble.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This event may have contributed to Alexander's failing health and detached mental state during his final months.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's sexuality has been the subject of speculation and controversy in modern times.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] The Roman era writer Athenaeus says, based on the scholar Dicaearchus, who was Alexander's contemporary, that the king "was quite excessively keen on boys", and that Alexander kissed the eunuch Bagoas in public.
[src:ancient-greece-ancient-india-relations/alexander-the-great-p02] This episode is also told by Plutarch, probably based on the same source.
